# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: baltimore-maryland
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] The land that is present-day Baltimore was once used as hunting ground by Paleo-Indians.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] In the early 1600s, the Susquehannock began to hunt there.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] People from the Province of Maryland established the Port of Baltimore in 1706 to support the tobacco trade with Europe and established the Town of Baltimore in 1729.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] The Battle of Baltimore was pivotal during the War of 1812, culminating in the British bombardment of Fort McHenry, during which Francis Scott Key wrote a poem that became "The Star-Spangled Banner", which was designated as the national anthem in 1931.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] During the Pratt Street Riot of 1861, the city was the site of some of the earliest violence associated with the American Civil War.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] The Baltimore and Ohio Railroad, the nation's oldest, was built in 1830 and reinforced Baltimore's status as a transportation hub, giving producers in the Midwest and Appalachia access to the city's port.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Baltimore's Inner Harbor was the second-leading port of entry for immigrants to the U.S. after New York's Ellis Island, making Baltimore a major manufacturing center.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] After a decline in heavy industry and restructuring of the rail industry, Baltimore has shifted to a service-oriented economy.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Johns Hopkins Hospital and University are now the city's top employers.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Baltimore is also home to the Baltimore Orioles of Major League Baseball and the Baltimore Ravens of the National Football League.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] It is ranked as a Gamma− world city by the Globalization and World Cities Research Network.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] The city is home to some of the earliest National Register Historic Districts in the nation, including Fell's Point, Federal Hill, and Mount Vernon.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Baltimore has more public statues and monuments per capita than any other city in the U.S.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Nearly one third of the buildings (over 65,000) are designated as historic in the National Register, more than any other U.S. city.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Baltimore has 66 National Register Historic Districts and 33 local historic districts.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] The city is named after Cecil Calvert, 2nd Baron Baltimore, an English politician and lawyer who was a founding proprietor of the Province of Maryland.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] The Calverts took the title Barons Baltimore from Baltimore Manor, an estate they were granted by the Crown in County Longford as part of the plantations of Ireland.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Baltimore is an anglicization of *Baile an Tí Mhóir*, meaning "town of the big house" in Irish.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] The Baltimore area was inhabited by Native Americans since at least the 10th millennium BC, when Paleo-Indians first settled in the region.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] One Paleo-Indian site and several Archaic period and Woodland period archaeological sites have been identified in Baltimore, including four from the Late Woodland period.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] In December 2021, several Woodland period Native American artifacts were found in Herring Run Park in northeast Baltimore, dating 5,000 to 9,000 years ago.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] The finding followed a period of dormancy in Baltimore City archaeological findings which had persisted since the 1980s.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] During the Late Woodland period, the archaeological culture known as the Potomac Creek complex resided in the area from Baltimore south to the Rappahannock River in present-day Virginia.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] In the early 1600s, the immediate Baltimore vicinity was sparsely populated, if at all, by Native Americans.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] The Baltimore County area northward was used as hunting grounds by the Susquehannock living in the lower Susquehanna River valley.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] This Iroquoian-speaking people "controlled all of the upper tributaries of the Chesapeake" but "refrained from much contact with Powhatan in the Potomac region" and south into Virginia.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Pressured by the Susquehannock, the Piscataway tribe, an Algonquian-speaking people, stayed well south of the Baltimore area and inhabited primarily the north bank of the Potomac River in what are now Charles and southern Prince George's counties in the coastal areas south of the Fall Line.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] European colonization of Maryland began in earnest with the arrival of the merchant ship *The Ark* carrying 140 colonists at St.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Clement's Island in the Potomac River on March 25, 1634.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Europeans then began to settle the area further north, in what is now Baltimore County.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Since Maryland was a colony, Baltimore's streets were named to show loyalty to the mother country, e.g.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] King, Queen, King George and Caroline streets.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] The original county seat, known today as Old Baltimore, was located on Bush River within the present-day Aberdeen Proving Ground.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] The colonists engaged in sporadic warfare with the Susquehannock, whose numbers dwindled primarily from new infectious diseases, such as smallpox, endemic among the Europeans.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] In 1661, David Jones claimed the area known today as Jonestown on the east bank of the Jones Falls stream.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] The colonial General Assembly of Maryland created the Port of Baltimore at old Whetstone Point, now Locust Point, in 1706 for the tobacco trade.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] The Town of Baltimore, on the west side of the Jones Falls, was founded on August 8, 1729, when the Governor of Maryland signed an act allowing "the building of a Town on the North side of the Patapsco River".
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Surveyors began laying out the town on January 12, 1730.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] By 1752 the town had just 27 homes, including a church and two taverns.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Jonestown and Fells Point had been settled to the east.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] The three settlements, covering 60 acres (24 ha), became a commercial hub, and in 1768 were designated as the county seat.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] The first printing press was introduced to the city in 1765 by Nicholas Hasselbach, whose equipment was later used in the printing of Baltimore's first newspapers, *The Maryland Journal* and *The Baltimore Advertiser*, first published by William Goddard in 1773.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Baltimore grew swiftly in the 18th century, its plantations producing grain and tobacco for sugar-producing colonies in the Caribbean.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] The profit from sugar encouraged the cultivation of cane in the Caribbean and the importation of food by planters there.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Since Baltimore was the county seat, a courthouse was built in 1768 to serve both the city and county.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Its square was a center of community meetings and discussions.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Baltimore established its public market system in 1763.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Lexington Market, founded in 1782, is one of the oldest continuously operating public markets in the United States today.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Lexington Market was also a center of slave trading.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Enslaved Black people were sold at numerous sites through the downtown area, with sales advertised in *The Baltimore Sun*.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Both tobacco and sugar cane were labor-intensive crops.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] In 1774, Baltimore established the first post office system in what became the United States, and the first water company chartered in the newly independent nation, Baltimore Water Company, 1792.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Baltimore played a part in the American Revolution.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] City leaders such as Jonathan Plowman Jr. led many residents to resist British taxes, and merchants signed agreements refusing to trade with Britain.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] The Second Continental Congress met in the Henry Fite House from December 1776 to February 1777, effectively making the city the capital of the United States during this period.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Baltimore, Jonestown, and Fells Point were incorporated as the City of Baltimore in 1796–1797.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] The city remained a part of surrounding Baltimore County and continued to serve as its county seat from 1768 to 1851, after which it became an independent city.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] The British bombardment of Baltimore in 1814 inspired the U.S. national anthem, "The Star-Spangled Banner", and the construction of the Battle Monument, which became the city's official emblem.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] A distinctive local culture started to take shape, and a unique skyline peppered with churches and monuments developed.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Baltimore acquired its moniker "The Monumental City" after an 1827 visit to Baltimore by President John Quincy Adams.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Baltimore pioneered the use of gas lighting in 1816, and its population grew rapidly in the following decades, with concomitant development of culture and infrastructure.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] The construction of the federally funded National Road, which later became part of U.S.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Route 40, and the private Baltimore and Ohio Railroad (B. & O.) made Baltimore a major shipping and manufacturing center by linking the city with major markets in the Midwest.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] By 1820 its population had reached 60,000, and its economy had shifted from its base in tobacco plantations to sawmilling, shipbuilding, and textile production.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] These industries benefited from war but successfully shifted into infrastructure development during peacetime.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Baltimore had one of the worst riots of the antebellum South in 1835, when bad investments led to the Baltimore bank riot.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] It was these riots that led to the city being nicknamed "Mobtown".
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Soon after the city created the world's first dental college, the Baltimore College of Dental Surgery, in 1840, and shared in the world's first telegraph line, between Baltimore and Washington, D.C., in 1844.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Maryland, a slave state with limited popular support for secession, especially in the three counties of Southern Maryland, remained part of the Union during the American Civil War, following the 55–12 vote by the Maryland General Assembly against secession.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] In February 1861, a plot in Baltimore to assassinate President-elect Abraham Lincoln was foiled by agents of the Pinkerton National Detective Agency.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Lincoln was able to pass through the city unnoticed, and arrived in Washington to be inaugurated a little more than a week later.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Later, the Union's strategic occupation of the city in 1861 ensured Maryland would not further consider secession.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] The Union's capital of Washington, D.C. was well-situated to impede Baltimore and Maryland's communication or commerce with the Confederacy.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Baltimore experienced some of the first casualties of the Civil War on April 19, 1861, when Union Army soldiers en route from President Street Station to Camden Yards clashed with a secessionist mob in the Pratt Street riot.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] In the midst of the Long Depression that followed the Panic of 1873, the Baltimore and Ohio Railroad company attempted to lower its workers' wages, leading to strikes and riots in the city and beyond.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Strikers clashed with the National Guard, leaving 10 dead and 25 wounded. settlement movement work in Baltimore began in 1893 with the founding of the Lawrence House on West Lombard Street.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] On February 7, 1904, the Great Baltimore Fire destroyed more than 1,500 buildings and left over 70 blocks of downtown Baltimore burned to the ground.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Damage was estimated at $150 million in 1904 dollars.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Rebuilding over the following years included improvements in firefighting equipment standards.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] In 1910, Baltimore enacted a residential segregation ordinance that restricted African-Americans from moving into majority-White blocks, and White residents from moving into majority-Black blocks.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] It was the first ordinance of its kind in the United States and became a model for similar laws in other southern cities, although the U.S.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Supreme Court later ruled such ordinances unconstitutional in *Buchanan v.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Baltimore expanded through annexations until 1918, when it acquired portions of Baltimore County and Anne Arundel County.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] A 1948 state constitutional amendment required a local vote in any area proposed for annexation, effectively preventing further expansion of the city's boundaries.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] During the mid-20th century, migration from the Deep South and white suburbanization changed the city's demographics: the Black share of the population rose from 23.8% in 1950 to 46.4% in 1970.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] The Baltimore riot of 1968 followed the assassination of Martin Luther King Jr. on April 4, 1968.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Public order was not restored until April 12, and National Guard and federal troops were sent into the city.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] In 1974, the city again faced major disruption when teachers, municipal workers, and police officers went on strike.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] By the early 1970s, the Inner Harbor had declined into an area of abandoned warehouses.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Redevelopment began with projects such as the Maryland Science Center in 1976, the Baltimore World Trade Center in 1977, and the Baltimore Convention Center in 1979.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Harborplace opened in 1980, followed by the National Aquarium and the Baltimore Museum of Industry in 1981.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] In 1992, the Baltimore Orioles moved from Memorial Stadium to Oriole Park at Camden Yards, near the Inner Harbor.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] The Baltimore Ravens later moved into M&T Bank Stadium, next to Camden Yards, in 1998.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Baltimore has seen the reopening of the Hippodrome Theatre in 2004, the opening of the Reginald F.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Lewis Museum of Maryland African American History & Culture in 2005, and the establishment of the National Slavic Museum in 2012.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] In April 2012, Johns Hopkins dedicated a $1.1 billion expansion of the Johns Hopkins Hospital, among the largest medical complexes in the United States, comprising the Sheikh Zayed Cardiovascular and Critical Care Tower and the Charlotte R.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] In September 2016, the Baltimore City Council approved a $660 million bond deal for the $5.5 billion Port Covington redevelopment project championed by Under Armour founder Kevin Plank and his real estate company Sagamore Development.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Port Covington surpassed the Harbor Point development as the largest tax-increment financing deal in Baltimore's history and among the largest urban redevelopment projects in the country.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] The waterfront development includes a new headquarters for Under Armour along with shops, housing, offices, and manufacturing space.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] In the early hours of March 26, 2024, the city's 1.6-mile (2.6 km) Francis Scott Key Bridge, which constituted a southeast portion of the Baltimore Beltway, was struck by a container ship and completely collapsed.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] A major rescue operation was launched with US authorities attempting to rescue people in the water.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Eight construction workers, who were working on the bridge at the time, fell into the Patapsco River.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Two people were rescued from the water, and the bodies of the remaining six were all found by May 7.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Replacement of the bridge was estimated in May 2024 at a cost approaching $2 billion for a fall 2028 completion.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Baltimore is in north-central Maryland on the Patapsco River, close to where it empties into the Chesapeake Bay.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Baltimore is located on the fall line between the Piedmont Plateau and the Atlantic coastal plain, which divides Baltimore into "lower city" and "upper city".
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Baltimore's elevation ranges from sea level at the harbor to 480 feet (150 m) in the northwest corner near Pimlico.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] In the 2010 census, Baltimore has a total area of 92.1 square miles (239 km2), of which 80.9 sq mi (210 km2) is land and 11.1 sq mi (29 km2) is water.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Baltimore is almost entirely surrounded by Baltimore County, but is politically independent of it.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] It is bordered by Anne Arundel County to the south.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Baltimore exhibits examples from each period of architecture over more than two centuries, and work from architects such as Benjamin Latrobe, George A.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Frederick, John Russell Pope, Mies van der Rohe, and I.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Baltimore is rich in architecturally significant buildings in a variety of styles.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] The Baltimore Basilica (1806–1821) is a neoclassical design by Benjamin Latrobe, and one of the oldest Catholic cathedrals in the United States.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] In 1813, Robert Cary Long Sr. built for Rembrandt Peale the first substantial structure in the United States designed expressly as a museum.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Restored, it is now the Municipal Museum of Baltimore, or popularly the Peale Museum.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] The Phoenix Shot Tower (1828), at 234.25 feet (71.40 m) tall, was the tallest building in the United States until the time of the Civil War, and is one of few remaining structures of its kind.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] It was constructed without the use of exterior scaffolding.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Hatfield in 1851, was the city's first iron-front building and was a model for a whole generation of downtown buildings.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Brown Memorial Presbyterian Church, built in 1870 in memory of financier George Brown, has stained glass windows by Louis Comfort Tiffany and has been called "one of the most significant buildings in this city, a treasure of art and architecture" by *Baltimore* magazine.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] The 1845 Greek Revival-style Lloyd Street Synagogue is one of the oldest synagogues in the United States.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] The Johns Hopkins Hospital, designed by Lt.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Billings in 1876, was a considerable achievement for its day in functional arrangement and fireproofing.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Pei's World Trade Center (1977) is the tallest equilateral pentagonal building in the world at 405 feet (123 m) tall.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] The streets of Baltimore are organized in a grid and spoke pattern, lined with tens of thousands of rowhouses whose mix of brick and formstone facings gives the city a distinct look; the latter was a technology patented in 1937 by Albert Knight.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] John Waters characterized formstone as "the polyester of brick".
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Developers began building entire neighborhoods of rowhouses in the mid-1790s, and the form became the dominant house type of the city early in the 19th century.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Oriole Park at Camden Yards is a Major League Baseball park, which opened in 1992 and was built as a retro style baseball park.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Along with the National Aquarium, Camden Yards have helped revive the Inner Harbor area from what once was an exclusively industrial district full of dilapidated warehouses into a bustling commercial district full of bars, restaurants, and retail establishments.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Baltimore is commonly divided into nine geographic regions: North, Northeast, East, Southeast, South, Southwest, West, Northwest, and Central, each corresponding to a Baltimore Police Department district.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] I-83 and Charles Street to Hanover Street and Ritchie Highway serve as a rough east–west dividing line, while Eastern Avenue to Route 40 serves as a north–south divider; for the U.S.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Postal Service, Baltimore Street is the north–south dividing line.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] North Baltimore contains historic neighborhoods such as Govans, Roland Park, Guilford, Homeland, Hampden, Charles Village, and Mount Washington, as well as the Station North Arts and Entertainment District.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] South Baltimore and Southeast Baltimore include mixed residential, industrial, and waterfront neighborhoods such as Federal Hill, Locust Point, Fells Point, Canton, Highlandtown, Little Italy, and Greektown.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Landmarks in these areas include Fort McHenry, Patterson Park, the Highlandtown Arts District, and Johns Hopkins Bayview Medical Center.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Northeast Baltimore is largely residential and includes Morgan State University, Baltimore City College, the former site of Memorial Stadium, and Lake Montebello.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] East Baltimore includes Johns Hopkins Hospital, the Johns Hopkins University School of Medicine, and neighborhoods such as Armistead Gardens, Broadway East, Barclay, and McElderry Park.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Northwest Baltimore includes Pimlico Race Course, Sinai Hospital, the headquarters of the NAACP, and neighborhoods such as Pimlico, Mount Washington, Cheswolde, and Park Heights.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] West Baltimore includes the Old West Baltimore Historic District, historically a center of the city's Black community, as well as Coppin State University, Mondawmin Mall, and Edmondson Village.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Southwest Baltimore includes Pigtown, Carrollton Ridge, Ridgely's Delight, Leakin Park, and St.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Baltimore is bordered by the following communities, all unincorporated census-designated places.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Baltimore has a humid subtropical (Köppen: *Cfa*) or oceanic (Trewartha: *Doak*) climate, with hot summers, cool winters, and a summer peak to annual precipitation.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Baltimore is part of USDA plant hardiness zones 7b and 8a.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Summers are hot and humid, with a daily average in July of 80.7 °F (27.1 °C) and occasional late-day thunderstorms.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Spring and autumn are mild, with spring the wettest season by number of precipitation days.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Winters range from chilly to mild, with sporadic snowfall: January has a daily average of 35.8 °F (2.1 °C), though temperatures reach 50 °F (10 °C) quite often and can occasionally drop below 20 °F (−7 °C) when Arctic air masses affect the area.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] According to *Vox*, winters are warming faster than summers.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] A southeasterly bay breeze off the Chesapeake often occurs on summer afternoons; interacting with prevailing southwesterly winds and the city's urban heat island, it can exacerbate air quality.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] In late summer and early autumn, hurricanes or their remnants may cause flooding in downtown Baltimore, despite the city being far removed from the typical coastal storm surge areas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] The average seasonal snowfall is 19 inches (48 cm).
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] It varies greatly by year, with some seasons seeing only trace accumulations of snow, while others see several major Nor'easters.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Owing to lessened urban heat island (UHI) as compared to the city proper and distance from the moderating Chesapeake Bay, the outlying and inland parts of the Baltimore metro area are usually cooler, especially at night, than the city proper and the coastal towns.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Thus, in the northern and western suburbs, winter snowfall is more significant, and some areas average more than 30 in (76 cm) of snow per winter.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] It is common in winter for the rain-snow line to set up in the metro area, and freezing rain and sleet occur a few times some winters.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Like all of Maryland, Baltimore is at risk for increased impacts of climate change.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Historically, flooding has ruined houses and almost killed people, especially in lower income majority Black neighborhoods, and caused sewage backups, given the existing disrepair of Baltimore's water system.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Extreme temperatures have ranged from −7 °F (−22 °C), most recently on January 22, 1984, up to 108 °F (42 °C) on July 22, 2011.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] On average, temperatures of 100 °F (38 °C) or more occur on three days annually, 90 °F (32 °C) or more on 43 days, and there are nine days where the high fails to reach the freezing mark.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Baltimore reached a peak population of 949,708 at the 1950 U.S. census count.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] In every ten-year census count since then, the city has lost population, with its 2020 census population at 585,708.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Baltimore is the most populous independent city in the United States.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] In 2020, Baltimore lost more population than any other major city in the United States.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] The population increased for the first time in decades in 2024.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Gentrification has increased since the 2000 census, primarily in East Baltimore, downtown, and Central Baltimore, with 14.8% of census tracts having had income growth and home values appreciation at a rate higher than the city overall.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Many, but not all, gentrifying neighborhoods are predominantly white areas which have seen a turnover from lower income to higher income households.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] These areas represent either expansion of existing gentrified areas, or activity around the Inner Harbor, downtown, or the Johns Hopkins Homewood campus.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] In some neighborhoods in East Baltimore, the Hispanic population has increased, while both the non-Hispanic white and non-Hispanic black populations have declined.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] After New York City, Baltimore was the second city in the United States to reach a population of 100,000.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] It was the second most-populous U.S. city from 1820 to 1850, and remained among the ten largest in every census through 1980.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] After World War II, the city's population approached one million before beginning its decline after the 1950 census.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Note: the US Census treats Hispanic/Latino as an ethnic category.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] This table excludes Latinos from the racial categories and assigns them to a separate category.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] In the 2010 census, Baltimore's population was 63.7% Black, 29.6% White (the largest ancestries being German, Italian, and Irish), 2.3% Asian, and 0.4% Native American and Alaska Native.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Across races, 4.2% of the population were of Hispanic, Latino, or Spanish origin, most commonly Salvadoran and Mexican.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] As per the 2020 census, 8.1% of residents between 2016 and 2020 were foreign born persons.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Females made up 53.4% of the population.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] The median age was 35 years old, with 22.4% under 18 years old, 65.8% from 18 to 64 years old, and 11.8% 65 or older.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Baltimore has a large Caribbean American population, with the largest groups being Jamaicans and Trinidadians.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Baltimore's Jamaican community is largely centered in the Park Heights neighborhood, but generations of immigrants have also lived in Southeast Baltimore.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] In 2005, approximately 30,778 people (6.5%) identified as gay, lesbian, or bisexual.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] In 2012, same-sex marriage in Maryland was legalized, going into effect January 1, 2013.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Between 2016 and 2020, the median household income was $52,164 and the median income per capita was $32,699, compared to the national averages of $64,994 and $35,384, respectively.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] In 2009, the median household income was $42,241 and the median income per capita was $25,707, compared to the national median income of $53,889 per household and $28,930 per capita.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] In 2009, 23.7% of the population lived below the poverty line, compared to 13.5% nationwide.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] In the 2020 census, 20% of Baltimore residents were living in poverty, compared to 11.6% nationwide.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Housing in Baltimore is relatively inexpensive for large, near-coastal cities of its size.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] The median sale price for homes in Baltimore as of December 2022 was $209,000, up from $95,000 in 2012.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Despite the late 2000s housing price collapse, and along with the national trends, Baltimore residents still faced slowly increasing rent, up 3% in the summer of 2010.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] The median value of owner-occupied housing units between 2016 and 2020 was $242,499.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] The homeless population in Baltimore is steadily increasing.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] The increase in the number of young homeless people was particularly severe.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] In 2015, the life expectancy in Baltimore was 74 to 75 years, compared to the U.S. average of 78 to 80.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Fourteen neighborhoods, concentrated in East, West, and South Baltimore, had lower life expectancies than North Korea, and the figure in Seton Hill was comparable to that of Yemen.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] In 2015, 25% of adults in Baltimore reported affiliation with no religion.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] 50% of the adult population of Baltimore are Protestants.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Catholicism is the second-largest religious affiliation, constituting 15% percent of the population, followed by Judaism (3%) and Islam (2%).
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Around 1% identify with other Christian denominations.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] In 2010, 91% (526,705) of Baltimore residents five years old and older spoke only English at home.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Other languages, such as African languages, French, and Chinese are spoken by less than 1% of the population.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Once a predominantly industrial town, with an economic base focused on steel processing, shipping, auto manufacturing (General Motors Baltimore Assembly), and transportation, Baltimore experienced deindustrialization, which cost residents tens of thousands of low-skill, high-wage jobs.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Baltimore now relies on a low-wage service economy, which accounts for 31% of jobs in the city.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Around the turn of the 20th century, Baltimore was the leading U.S. manufacturer of rye whiskey and straw hats.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] It led in the refining of crude oil, brought to the city by pipeline from Pennsylvania.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] In March 2018, Baltimore's unemployment rate was 5.8%.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] In 2012, one quarter of Baltimore residents, and 37% of Baltimore children, lived in poverty.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] The city is home to the Johns Hopkins Hospital.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Other large companies in Baltimore include Under Armour, BRT Laboratories, Cordish Company, Legg Mason, McCormick & Company, T.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] A sugar refinery owned by American Sugar Refining is one of Baltimore's cultural icons.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Nonprofits based in Baltimore include Lutheran Services in America, Catholic Relief Services and Jhpiego.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Almost a quarter of the jobs in the Baltimore region were in science, technology, engineering, and mathematics as of mid-2013, a fact attributed in part to the city's extensive undergraduate and graduate schools; maintenance and repair experts were included in this count.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] The center of international commerce for the region is the World Trade Center Baltimore, which houses the Maryland Port Administration and U.S. headquarters for major shipping lines.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Among all U.S. ports, Baltimore is ranked 9th for total dollar value of cargo and 13th for cargo tonnage.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] In 2014, cargo moving through the port totaled 29.5 million tons valued at $52.5 billion.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] The Port of Baltimore generates $3 billion in annual wages and salary, supports 14,630 direct jobs and 108,000 jobs connected to port work, and in 2014 generated more than $300 million in taxes.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] The port serves over 50 ocean carriers, making nearly 1,800 annual visits.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Among all U.S. ports, Baltimore is first in handling automobiles, light trucks, farm and construction machinery; and imported forest products, aluminum, and sugar.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] The Port of Baltimore's cruise industry, which offers year-round trips on several lines, supports over 400 jobs and brings in over $63 million to Maryland's economy annually.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Baltimore's history and attractions have made it a popular tourist destination.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] In 2014, the city hosted 24.5 million visitors, who spent $5.2 billion.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Much of the city's tourism centers around the Inner Harbor, with the National Aquarium being Maryland's top tourist destination.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] Baltimore Harbor's restoration has made it "a city of boats", with several historic ships maintained by the Historic Ships in Baltimore organization and open to the public.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p01] The Inner Harbor is also the home port of *Pride of Baltimore II*, the state's "goodwill ambassador" ship and a reconstruction of a famous Baltimore Clipper.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Baltimore has historically been a working-class port town, sometimes dubbed a "city of neighborhoods".
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] It comprises 72 designated historic districts traditionally occupied by distinct ethnic groups.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Further inland, Mount Vernon is the traditional center of cultural and artistic life of the city.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] It is home to a distinctive Washington Monument, set atop a hill in a 19th-century urban square, that predates the monument in Washington, D.C. by several decades.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Baltimore has a significant German American population, and was the second-largest port of immigration to the United States behind Ellis Island in New York and New Jersey.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Between 1820 and 1989, almost 2 million migrants—among them German, Polish, English, Irish, Russian, Lithuanian, Greek and Italian—came to Baltimore, mostly between 1861 and 1930.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] By 1913 the city was averaging forty thousand immigrants per year, until World War I closed off the flow.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] A Chinatown dating to at least the 1880s once held some 400 Chinese residents; a local Chinese-American association remains based there.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Beer making thrived in Baltimore from the 1800s to the 1950s, with over 100 breweries in the city's past.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The best remaining examples are the old American Brewery Building on North Gay Street and the National Brewing Company building in Brewer's Hill.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] In the 1940s the National Brewing Company introduced the nation's first six-pack; its two most prominent brands were National Bohemian Beer (colloquially "Natty Boh") and Colt 45.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Both are still made today, albeit outside Maryland, and remain local staples whose "Natty Boh" mascot appears on merchandise throughout the area.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Each year the Artscape takes place in the city in the Bolton Hill neighborhood, close to the Maryland Institute College of Art.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Artscape styles itself as the "largest free arts festival in America".
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Each May, the Maryland Film Festival takes place in Baltimore, using all five screens of the historic Charles Theatre as its anchor venue.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Many movies and television shows have been filmed in Baltimore.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] *Homicide: Life on the Street* was set and filmed in Baltimore, as well as *The Wire.* *House of Cards* and *Veep* are set in Washington, D.C. but filmed in Baltimore.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Baltimore has cultural museums in many areas of study.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The Baltimore Museum of Art and the Walters Art Museum are internationally renowned for their collections of art.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The Baltimore Museum of Art has the largest holding of works by Henri Matisse in the world.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The American Visionary Art Museum has been designated by Congress as America's national museum for visionary art.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The National Great Blacks In Wax Museum is the first African American wax museum in the country, featuring more than 150 life-size and lifelike wax figures.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Baltimore is known for its Maryland blue crabs, crab cake, Old Bay Seasoning, pit beef, and the "chicken box" (chicken wings with french fries).
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The city has many restaurants in or around the Inner Harbor, with Little Italy and Fells Point—home to the country's oldest continuously running tavern, "The Horse You Came in on Saloon"—drawing tourists and locals alike.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The Baltimore Public Market System is the oldest continuously operating public market system in the United States, and Lexington Market, dating to 1782, is among the longest-running in the world.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Baltimore is also the last place in America with arabbers, vendors who sell produce from horse-drawn carts.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] In 2015, Zagat ranked Baltimore second on a list of the 17 best food cities in the U.S.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Baltimore city, along with its surrounding regions, is home to a unique local dialect known as the Baltimore dialect.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] It is part of the larger Mid-Atlantic American English group and is noted to be very similar to the Philadelphia dialect.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The so-called "Bawlmerese" (named so for how locals often pronounce the city as "Bawlmore") accent is known for its characteristic pronunciation of its long "o" vowel, in which an "eh" sound is added before the long "o" sound (/oʊ/ shifts to [ɘʊ], or even [eʊ]).
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] It adopts Philadelphia's pattern of the short "a" sound, such that the tensed vowel in words like "bath" or "ask" does not match the more relaxed one in "sad" or "act".
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Baltimore native John Waters parodies the city and its dialect extensively in his films.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Most are filmed in Baltimore, including the 1972 cult classic *Pink Flamingos*, as well as *Hairspray* and its Broadway musical remake.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Baltimore has four state-designated arts and entertainment districts: The Pennsylvania Avenue Black Arts and Entertainment District, Station North Arts and Entertainment District, Highlandtown Arts District, and the Bromo Arts & Entertainment District.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The Baltimore Office of Promotion and the Arts (BOPA), the official city arts council, produces arts programs, manages several facilities, and coordinates major events such as the Inner Harbor's New Year's Eve and July 4 celebrations, Artscape, the Baltimore Book Festival, and the Dr.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The Baltimore Symphony Orchestra is an internationally renowned orchestra, founded in 1916 as a publicly funded municipal organization.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Its most recent music director was Marin Alsop, a protégé of Leonard Bernstein's.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Centerstage is the premier theater company in the city and a regionally well-respected group.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The Lyric Opera House is the home of Lyric Opera Baltimore, which operates there as part of the Patricia and Arthur Modell Performing Arts Center.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Shriver Hall Concert Series, founded in 1966, presents classical chamber music and recitals featuring nationally and internationally recognized artists.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The Peabody Institute, located in the Mount Vernon neighborhood, is the oldest conservatory of music in the United States.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Established in 1857, it is one of the most prestigious in the world, along with Juilliard, Eastman, and the Curtis Institute.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The Morgan State University Choir is one of the nation's most prestigious university choral ensembles.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The city is also home to the Baltimore School for the Arts, a public high school in Mount Vernon nationally recognized for preparing students in music, theatre, dance, and visual arts.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] In 1981, Baltimore hosted the first International Theater Festival, staging 66 performances of nine shows by international theatre companies; the event proved expensive and moved to Denver the following year.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] In June 1986, the 20th Theatre of Nations, sponsored by the International Theatre Institute, was held in Baltimore, the first time it had taken place in the U.S.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Baltimore has a long and storied baseball history, including its distinction as the birthplace of Babe Ruth in 1895.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The original 19th-century Baltimore Orioles (1882–1899) were among the most successful early franchises.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] A short-lived American League Orioles played in 1901–1902 before moving to New York and becoming the New York Yankees, while Ruth played for the minor-league Orioles, who competed locally until 1953.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The team currently known as the Baltimore Orioles has represented Major League Baseball locally since 1954 when the St.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] In 1995, local player (and later Hall of Famer) Cal Ripken Jr. broke Lou Gehrig's streak of 2,130 consecutive games played, for which Ripken was named Sportsman of the Year by *Sports Illustrated* magazine.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Six former Orioles players, including Ripken (2007), and two of the team's managers have been inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Since 1992, the Orioles' home ballpark has been Oriole Park at Camden Yards, which has been hailed as one of the league's best since it opened.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Before the 1950s, several attempts at a professional football team in Baltimore were blocked by the Washington franchise and its NFL allies.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The first major-league team in the city was the All-America Football Conference (AAFC) Baltimore Colts, which played from 1947 to 1949, joined the NFL for a single year (1950), and then went bankrupt.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] In 1953, the NFL's Dallas Texans folded.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Its assets and player contracts were purchased by an ownership team headed by Baltimore businessman Carroll Rosenbloom, who moved the team to Baltimore, establishing a new team also named the Baltimore Colts.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] During the 1950s and 1960s, the Colts were one of the NFLs more successful franchises, led by Pro Football Hall of Fame quarterback Johnny Unitas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The Colts advanced to the NFL Championship twice (1958 and 1959) and the Super Bowl twice (1969 and 1971), winning all except Super Bowl III in 1969.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] After the 1983 season, the team left Baltimore for Indianapolis in 1984, where they became the Indianapolis Colts.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The NFL returned to Baltimore when the former Cleveland Browns personnel moved to Baltimore and established the Baltimore Ravens in 1996.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Baltimore also hosted a Canadian Football League franchise, the Baltimore Stallions for the 1994 and 1995 seasons.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Following the 1995 season, and ultimate end to the Canadian Football League in the United States experiment, the team was sold and relocated to Montreal.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The first professional sports organization in the United States, The Maryland Jockey Club, was formed in Baltimore in 1743.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Preakness Stakes, the second race in the United States Triple Crown of Thoroughbred Racing, has been held every May at Pimlico Race Course in Baltimore since 1873.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] College lacrosse is a common sport in the spring, as the Johns Hopkins Blue Jays men's lacrosse team has won 44 national championships, the most of any program in history.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] In addition, Loyola University won its first men's NCAA lacrosse championship in 2012.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The Baltimore Blast are a professional arena soccer team that play in the Major Arena Soccer League at the SECU Arena on the campus of Towson University.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The Blast have won nine championships in various leagues, including the MASL; a previous Blast franchise played in the Major Indoor Soccer League from 1980 to 1992, winning one championship.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Other local clubs have included the semi-professional soccer sides FC Baltimore 1729 (founded 2018 in the National Premier Soccer League) and the Baltimore Bohemians, and Baltimore City F.C., an American Premier Soccer League club playing since 2023 at Utz Field in Patterson Park.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The Baltimore Blues were a semi-professional rugby league club that began competition in the USA Rugby League in 2012.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The Baltimore Grand Prix ran along the streets of downtown's Inner Harbor from 2011 to 2013, hosting the American Le Mans Series and IndyCar Series before being discontinued over scheduling conflicts.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The Baltimore Marathon, the flagship of several races, begins and ends at Camden Yards, winding through neighborhoods including the Inner Harbor, Federal Hill, Fells Point, Canton, and Patterson Park.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The Baltimore Brigade were an Arena Football League team based in Baltimore that, from 2017 to 2019, played at Royal Farms Arena.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] In 2019, the team ceased operations along with the rest of the league.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Baltimore has over 4,900 acres (1,983 ha) of parkland.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The Baltimore City Department of Recreation and Parks manages the majority of parks and recreational facilities in the city, including Patterson Park, Federal Hill Park, and Druid Hill Park.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Gwynns Falls/Leakin Park, the city's most extensive park, is also the second-largest urban woodland in the nation.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The city is home to Fort McHenry National Monument and Historic Shrine, a coastal star-shaped fort best known for its role in the War of 1812.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] As of 2015, The Trust for Public Land, a national land conservation organization, ranks Baltimore 40th among the 75-largest U.S. cities.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Baltimore is an independent city, and not part of any county.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] For most governmental purposes under Maryland law, Baltimore City is treated as a county-level entity.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The United States Census Bureau uses counties as the basic unit for presentation of statistical information in the United States, and treats Baltimore as a county equivalent for those purposes.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Hirsch Goldberg, a former press secretary for a mayor of the city, stated in the *Baltimore Sun* that because Baltimore is not in a county, there is no county-wide government that could assist the city, and that the city does not have as much political representation in the Maryland Legislature.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Goldberg argued that the status of not being in a county, along with the total square mileage, which he characterized as small, was damaging the city's fortunes.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Baltimore has been a Democratic stronghold for over 150 years, with Democrats dominating every level of government.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] In virtually all elections, the Democratic primary is the real contest.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] As of the 2020 elections, registered Democrats outnumbered registered Republicans by almost 10-to-1.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] No Republican has been elected to the City Council since 1939.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The city's last Republican mayor, Theodore McKeldin, left office in 1967.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] No Republican candidate since then has received 30 percent or more of the vote.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] In the 2016 and 2020 mayoral elections, the Republicans were pushed into third place by write-in and independent candidates, respectively.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The last Republican candidate for president to win the city was Dwight Eisenhower in his successful reelection bid in 1956.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The city hosted the first six Democratic National Conventions, from 1832 through 1852, and hosted the DNC again in 1860, 1872, and 1912.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Brandon Scott is the current mayor of Baltimore.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] He was elected in 2020 and took office on December 8, 2020.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Scott succeeded Jack Young, who became acting mayor in April 2019 and then mayor upon the resignation of Catherine Pugh, who left office amid a self-dealing book-sales scandal.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Pugh, a Democrat, had won the 2016 election with 57.1% of the vote.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Stephanie Rawlings-Blake, previously City Council President, became mayor in February 2010 upon Dixon's resignation and won a full term in 2011.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Sheila Dixon, Baltimore's first female mayor, had taken office in 2007 after Martin O'Malley became governor; she resigned in 2010 following an embezzlement conviction and an Alford plea to a perjury charge, as Maryland does not allow convicted felons to hold office.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The Baltimore City Council is made up of 14 members elected from single-member districts and a council president elected at-large.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The council president is *ex officio* mayor pro tempore; if the mayor's office falls vacant, the council president ascends as mayor for the balance of the term.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Grassroots pressure for reform, voiced as Question P, restructured the city council in November 2002, against the will of the mayor, the council president, and the majority of the council.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] A coalition of union and community groups, organized by the Association of Community Organizations for Reform Now (ACORN), backed the effort.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The Baltimore City Police Department is the primary law enforcement agency serving Baltimore.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] It began in 1784 as a night watch and day constable system, was reorganized as a city department in 1853, and came under State of Maryland supervision in 1859.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Campus and building security for the city's public schools is provided by the Baltimore City Public Schools Police, established in the 1970s.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] In 2015, Baltimore agreed to pay $6.4 million to settle civil claims by the family of Freddie Gray, a sum greater than the combined settlements from 120 police brutality and misconduct lawsuits filed from 2011 to 2015.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Baltimore has had a high violent-crime and homicide rate for decades, even as overall reported crime fell substantially from the mid-1990s to the mid-2010s.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Homicides peaked at 353 in 1993 and reached 344 in 2015, when the city recorded its highest homicide rate because its population had declined.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] After remaining above 300 annually from 2016 through 2022, homicides declined to 263 in 2023 and 200 in 2024.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Baltimore is protected by the over 1,800 professional firefighters of the Baltimore City Fire Department (BCFD), founded in 1858 to replace the city's warring volunteer companies.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The BCFD operates out of 37 fire stations throughout the city.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Since the legislative redistricting in 2002, Baltimore has had six legislative districts located entirely within its boundaries, giving the city six seats in the 47-member Maryland Senate and 14 in the 141-member Maryland House of Delegates.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] During the previous 10-year period, Baltimore had four legislative districts within the city limits, but four others overlapped the Baltimore County line.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] As of October 2024, all of Baltimore's state senators and delegates were Democrats.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Baltimore is split between two of the state's eight congressional districts.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Most of the city is included in the 7th district, represented by Kweisi Mfume.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] A sliver of northern Baltimore is located in the 2nd district, represented by Johnny Olszewski.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] A Republican has not represented a significant portion of Baltimore in Congress since John Boynton Philip Clayton Hill represented the 3rd District in 1927, and has not represented any of Baltimore since the Eastern Shore-based 1st District lost its share of Baltimore after the 2000 census.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] It was represented by Republican Wayne Gilchrest at the time.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Maryland's former United States senator Ben Cardin is from Baltimore.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] He was one of three people who, over four decades, represented the 3rd District—long including much of inner Baltimore—before election to the U.S.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Senate, the others being Paul Sarbanes and Barbara Mikulski.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The Postal Service's Baltimore Main Post Office is located at 900 East Fayette Street in the Jonestown area.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The national headquarters for the United States Social Security Administration is located in Woodlawn, just outside of Baltimore.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Baltimore is the home of numerous places of higher learning, both public and private.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] 100,000 college students from around the country attend Baltimore City's 10 accredited two-year or four-year colleges and universities.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The city's public schools are managed by Baltimore City Public Schools.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Notable among them are Frederick Douglass High School, the second-oldest African American high school in the United States; Baltimore City College, the third-oldest public high school in the nation; and Western High School, the oldest public all-girls school in the nation.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Baltimore City College and Baltimore Polytechnic Institute share the nation's second-oldest high school football rivalry.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Baltimore has a higher-than-average percentage of households without a car.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] In 2015, 30.7 percent of Baltimore households lacked a car, which decreased slightly to 28.9 percent in 2016.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The national average was 8.7 percent in 2016.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Baltimore averaged 1.65 cars per household in 2016, compared to a national average of 1.8.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Baltimore's highway growth has done much to influence the development of the city and its suburbs.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The first limited-access highway serving Baltimore was the Baltimore–Washington Parkway, which opened in stages between 1950 and 1954; its maintenance is split between the state of Maryland and the National Park Service, and trucks are restricted to its northern part.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Route 1 until Interstate 95 between Baltimore and Washington opened in 1971.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The Interstate highways serving Baltimore are I-70, I-83 (the Jones Falls Expressway), I-95, I-395, I-695 (the Baltimore Beltway), I-795 (the Northwest Expressway), I-895 (the Harbor Tunnel Thruway), and I-97.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The city's mainline Interstate highways—I-95, I-83, and I-70—do not directly connect to each other, and in the case of I-70 end at a park and ride lot just inside the city limits, because of freeway revolts in Baltimore.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] These revolts were led primarily by Barbara Mikulski, a former United States senator for Maryland, which resulted in the abandonment of the original plan.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] There are two tunnels traversing Baltimore Harbor within the city limits: the four-bore Fort McHenry Tunnel (opened in 1985 and serving I-95) and the two-bore Harbor Tunnel (opened in 1957 and serving I-895).
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Until its collapse in March 2024, the Baltimore Beltway crossed south of Baltimore Harbor over the Francis Scott Key Bridge.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Planning for the Baltimore Beltway predates the creation of the Interstate Highway System.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Highways in the city are US 1, which bypasses downtown, and US 40, which crosses downtown from east to west.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Both run along major surface streets, US 40 utilizes a small section of a freeway cancelled in the 1970s in the west side of the city, originally intended for Interstate 170.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] State routes in the city travel along surface streets, with the exception of Maryland Route 295, which carries the Baltimore–Washington Parkway.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The Baltimore City Department of Transportation (BCDOT) maintains the city's streets, sidewalks, and alleys, road signs, and street lights, and handles vehicle towing and traffic cameras.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Its responsibilities include the state and U.S. highways and the portions of I-83 and I-70 within the city limits; I-95, I-395, I-695, and I-895 are instead maintained by the Maryland Transportation Authority.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Public transit in Baltimore is mostly provided by the Maryland Transit Administration (abbreviated "MTA Maryland") and Charm City Circulator.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] MTA Maryland operates a comprehensive bus network, including many local, express, and commuter buses.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The Charm City Circulator (CCC), a free shuttle bus service operated for the Baltimore City Department of Transportation, began running in the downtown area in January 2010.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Funded partly by an increase in parking fees, it provides free service seven days a week across four color-coded routes linking downtown with Johns Hopkins Hospital, Fells Point, Federal Hill, Harbor East, and Fort McHenry.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Baltimore has a water taxi service, operated by Baltimore Water Taxi.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The water taxi's six routes provide service throughout the city's harbor, and was purchased by Under Armour CEO Kevin Plank's Sagamore Ventures in 2016.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] In June 2017, the BaltimoreLink bus network redesign was launched.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The BaltimoreLink redesign consisted of a dozen high frequency, color-coded routes branded CityLink, running every 10 to 15 minutes through downtown Baltimore, along with changes to local and express bus service, rebranded LocalLink and ExpressLink.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Baltimore is a top destination for Amtrak along the Northeast Corridor, and its Penn Station is one of the busiest in the country—ranked the seventh-busiest U.S. rail station as of 2014.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The corridor approaches from the south through the 1873 Baltimore and Potomac Tunnel, whose 30 mph (50 km/h) limit, sharp curves, and steep grades make it one of the NEC's worst bottlenecks, and from the north through the 1873 Union Tunnel.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Just outside the city, BWI Thurgood Marshall Airport Rail Station is another stop.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Scheduled Amtrak services include the *Acela Express*, *Northeast Regional*, and several long-distance trains such as the *Silver Star*, *Silver Meteor*, *Crescent*, and *Vermonter*.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] MARC commuter rail (the Brunswick, Camden, and Penn lines) connects Camden Station and Penn Station with Washington, D.C.'s Union Station and stops in between; the Penn Line added weekend service in 2013.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Baltimore is served by two airports, both operated by the Maryland Aviation Administration, which is part of the Maryland Department of Transportation.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Baltimore–Washington International Thurgood Marshall Airport, generally known as "BWI", is the main international airport in the Baltimore area.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] It lies about 10 miles (16 km) to the south of Baltimore in neighboring Anne Arundel County.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The airport is named after Thurgood Marshall, a Baltimore native who was the first African American to serve on the Supreme Court of the United States.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] In terms of passenger traffic, BWI is the 22nd busiest airport in the United States.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] As of 2014, BWI is the largest, by passenger count, of three major airports serving the Baltimore–Washington Metropolitan Area.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] It is accessible by I-95 and the Baltimore–Washington Parkway via Interstate 195, the Baltimore Light Rail, and Amtrak and MARC Train at BWI Rail Station.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Baltimore is also served by Martin State Airport, a general aviation facility, to the northeast in Baltimore County.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Martin State Airport is linked to downtown Baltimore by Maryland Route 150 (Eastern Avenue) and by MARC Train at its own station.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Baltimore has a comprehensive, signed system of unnumbered bicycle routes, with roads marked by bike lanes, sharrows, or Share the Road signs.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The network continues to expand, with over 140 miles (230 km) of lanes added between 2006 and 2014, and the city has also built bike boulevards, beginning with Guilford Avenue in 2012.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The city has three major trail systems—the Gwynns Falls Trail, the Jones Falls Trail, and the Herring Run Trail—the first two of which carry sections of the East Coast Greenway.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Protected cycle tracks on Maryland Avenue, Mount Royal Avenue, and Monument Street form the backbone of the downtown bicycle network, while the Stony Run Trail follows part of the old Ma and Pa Railroad corridor.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] A 2011 study by Walk Score ranked Baltimore the 14th-most walkable of the fifty largest U.S. cities.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The port was founded in 1706, preceding the founding of Baltimore.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The Maryland colonial legislature made the area near Locust Point as the port of entry for the tobacco trade with England.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Fells Point, the deepest point in the natural harbor, soon became the colony's main ship building center, later on becoming leader in the construction of clipper ships.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] After Baltimore's founding, mills were built behind the wharves, and the California Gold Rush brought orders for fast vessels.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] By the end of the nineteenth century, European ship lines maintained immigrant terminals there, and the Baltimore and Ohio Railroad made the port a major transshipment point.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The port has major roll-on/roll-off and bulk facilities, especially for steel handling.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Water taxis operate in the Inner Harbor.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Governor Ehrlich participated in naming the port after Helen Delich Bentley during the 300th anniversary of the port.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] In 2007, Duke Realty Corporation began the Chesapeake Commerce Center, a 184-acre (0.74 km2) industrial park on the site of a former General Motors plant in eastern Baltimore.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The Port of Baltimore is one of two East Coast seaports with a 50-foot (15 m) dredge able to accommodate the largest shipping vessels.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Baltimore has four water wheel trash interceptors for removing garbage in area waterways.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] One is at the mouth of Jones Falls in Baltimore's Inner Harbor, dubbed "Mr.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Another, "Professor Trash Wheel", was added at Harris Creek in the Canton neighborhood in 2016, with "Captain Trash Wheel" following at Mason Creek in 2018, and "Gwynnda, the Good Wheel of the West" at the mouth of the Gwynns Falls in 2021.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] A February 2015 agreement with a local waste-to-energy plant is believed to make Baltimore the first city to use reclaimed waterway debris to generate electricity.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] In August 2010, the National Aquarium assembled, planted, and launched a floating wetland island designed by Biohabitats in Baltimore's Inner Harbor.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Hundreds of years ago, Baltimore's harbor shoreline would have been lined with tidal wetlands.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Biohabitats also developed a concept to transform a dilapidated wharf into a living pier that cleans Harbor water, provides habitat and is an aesthetic attraction.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Currently under design, the top of the pier will become a constructed tidal wetland.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Other projects to improve water quality include the Blue Alleys project, expanded street sweeping, and stream restoration.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Since 1985 the Wheelabrator Baltimore incinerator, formerly known as the Baltimore Refuse Energy Systems Co., has operated as a waste-to-energy incinerator.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The incinerator is a significant source of air pollution to nearby neighborhoods.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Several environmental groups, such as the Environmental Integrity Project, and the Chesapeake Climate Action Network, have been successful in advocating for reinforced pollution monitoring.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The incinerator is the city's single largest standing source of air pollution.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Baltimore's main media outlet since 2010 is *The Baltimore Sun*, which was sold by its Baltimore owners in 1986 to the Times Mirror Company, and then bought by the Tribune Company in 2000.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Since the sale, *The Baltimore Sun* prints some local news along with regional and national articles.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The *Baltimore News-American*, another long-running paper that competed with the Sun, ceased publication in 1986.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The city is home to the Baltimore Afro-American, an influential African American newspaper founded in 1892.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] In 2006, *The Baltimore Examiner* was launched to compete with *The Sun*.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] It was part of a national chain that includes *The San Francisco Examiner* and *The Washington Examiner*.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] In contrast to the paid subscription *Sun*, *The Examiner* was a free newspaper funded solely by advertisements.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Unable to turn a profit and facing a deep recession, *The Baltimore Examiner* ceased publication on February 15, 2009.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Despite being located 40 miles northeast of Washington, D.C., Baltimore is a major media market in its own right, with all major English language television networks represented in the city.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] WJZ-TV 13 is a CBS owned and operated station, and WBFF 45 (Fox, with MyNetworkTV on DT2) is the flagship of Sinclair Broadcast Group, the second-largest station owner in the country.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Other major television stations in Baltimore include WMAR-TV 2 (ABC), WBAL-TV 11 (NBC), WUTB 24 (Roar), WNUV 54 (CW), and WMPB 67 (PBS).
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Baltimore is also served by low-power station WMJF-CD 39 (Ion), which transmits from the campus of Towson University.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Nielsen ranked Baltimore as the 27th-largest television market in 2009.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Arbitron's Fall 2010 rankings identified Baltimore as the 22nd-largest radio market.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Edgar Allan Poe lived in several different cities including Baltimore, which is where he died and was buried.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Several of his works were inspired and written during his time in the city including "MS.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Scott Fitzgerald—who had deep ties to Baltimore as a relative and namesake of Francis Scott Key—published the short story *The Curious Case of Benjamin Button*, about a man born in Baltimore who ages backwards.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Fitzgerald lived in the city for five years in the 1930s, partly so that Zelda could receive psychiatric care at Johns Hopkins and the Sheppard-Pratt Hospital; his first editor was the "Sage of Baltimore", H.L.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Anne Tyler has lived in Baltimore since the late 1960s and is known for her literary realism fiction that emphasizes family life.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] She has written a number of books set locally including *The Accidental Tourist* (1985), *Breathing Lessons* (1988), *Digging To America* (2006) and *A Spool of Blue Thread* (2015).
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] In 1845, Frederick Douglass published his memoir: *Narrative of the Life of Frederick Douglass, an American Slave*.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Born on the Eastern Shore, Douglass arrived in Baltimore as a child.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] It is where he learned to read and write.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] In 2008, journalist, novelist and activist Ta-Nehisi Coates published his memoir of growing up in West Baltimore: *The Beautiful Struggle.* Coates writes of his challenging relationship with his father, troubled experiences in local schools and the street crime and drug epidemic of the 1990s.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Barry Levinson is a film maker and a native Baltimorean.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Several of his films pay homage to his upbringing in an immigrant family in the city: *Diner* (1982), *Tin Men* (1987), *Avalon* (1990), and *Liberty Heights* (1999).
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Another Baltimore filmmaker, John Waters, began his career making experimental art films in the city including *Roman Candies* and *Mondo Trasho*.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] As his audience and film budgets expanded, Waters continued to set his films in Baltimore and to premier them at the Senator Theater.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Waters has continued to live in Baltimore and remains active in the local arts community.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The television representations of Baltimore often involve crime or law enforcement.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] From 1993 to 1998, the police procedural drama *Homicide: Life on the Street* aired with favorable reviews but low ratings.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Several episodes of the *X-Files* (1993–2002) took place in Baltimore.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] *The Corner* (2000) is a mini-series based on a true story of people living amid the open air drug markets of West Baltimore.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] The most known series set in Baltimore is *The Wire* (2002–2008), which was well-received and depicts the city as a war zone between drug trade and the police.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] In 2022, the limited drama series *We Own This City* premiered, starring Jon Bernthal and native Baltimorean Josh Charles.
[src:baltimore-maryland/baltimore-maryland-p02] Baltimore has ten sister cities, as designated by Sister Cities International.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Both Dallas and Fort Worth were initially developed as a product of the construction of major railroad lines through the area allowing access to cotton, cattle, and later oil in North and East Texas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The construction of the Interstate Highway System reinforced Dallas's prominence as a transportation hub, with four major interstate highways converging in the city and a fifth interstate loop around it.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Dallas then developed as a strong industrial and financial center and a major inland port, due to the convergence of major railroad lines, interstate highways, and the construction of Dallas Fort Worth International Airport, one of the largest and busiest airports in the world.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] In addition, Dallas Area Rapid Transit (DART) operates rail and bus transit services throughout the city and its surrounding suburbs.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Dominant sectors of its diverse economy include defense, financial services (such as traditional banking, investment banking, private equity, and venture capital), information technology, telecommunications, and transportation.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The Dallas–Fort Worth metroplex hosts 23 *Fortune* 500 companies, the second-most in Texas and fourth-most in the United States, and 11 of those companies are located within Dallas city limits.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Over 41 colleges and universities are located within its metropolitan area, which is the most of any metropolitan area in Texas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The city has a population from a myriad of ethnic and religious backgrounds.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Indigenous tribes in North Texas included the Caddo, Tawakoni, Wichita, Kickapoo and Comanche.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Spanish colonists claimed the territory of Texas in the 18th century as a part of the Viceroyalty of New Spain.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Later, France also claimed the area but never established much settlement.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] In all, six flags have flown over the area preceding and during the city's history: those of France, Spain, and Mexico, the flag of the Republic of Texas, the Confederate flag, and the flag of the United States of America.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] In 1819, the Adams–Onís Treaty between the United States and Spain defined the Red River as the northern boundary of New Spain, officially placing the future location of Dallas well within Spanish territory.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The area remained under Spanish rule until 1821, when Mexico declared independence from Spain, and the area was considered part of the Mexican state of Coahuila y Tejas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] In 1836, Texians, with a majority of Anglo-American settlers, gained independence from Mexico and formed the Republic of Texas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Three years after Texas achieved independence, John Neely Bryan surveyed the area around present-day Dallas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] In 1839, accompanied by his dog and a Cherokee he called Ned, he planted a stake in the ground on a bluff located near three forks of the Trinity River and left.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Two years later, in 1841, he returned to establish a permanent settlement named Dallas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The official historical marker states it was named after Vice President George M.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Other potential theories for the origin include his brother, Commodore Alexander James Dallas, as well as brothers Walter R.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] A further theory gives the ultimate origin as the village of Dallas, Moray, Scotland, similar to the way Houston, Texas, was named after Sam Houston, whose ancestors came from the Scottish village of Houston, Renfrewshire.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The Republic of Texas was annexed by the United States in 1845 and Dallas County was established the following year.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Dallas was formally incorporated as a city on February 2, 1856.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] In the mid-1800s, a group of French Socialists established La Réunion, a short-lived community, along the Trinity River in what is now West Dallas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] With the construction of railroads, Dallas became a business and trading center and was booming by the end of the 19th century.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] It became an industrial city, attracting workers from Texas, the South, and the Midwest.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The Praetorian Building in Dallas of 15 stories, built in 1909, was among the first skyscrapers west of the Mississippi and the tallest building in Texas for some time.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] It marked the prominence of Dallas as a city.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] A racetrack for thoroughbreds was built and their owners established the Dallas Jockey Club.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Trotters raced at a track in Fort Worth, where a similar drivers club was based.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The rapid expansion of population increased competition for jobs and housing.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] In 1910, a white mob of hundreds of people lynched a black man, Allen Brooks, accused of raping a little girl.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The mob tortured Brooks, then killed him at the downtown intersection of Main and Akard by hanging him from a decorative archway inscribed with the words "Welcome Visitors".
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Thousands of Dallasites came to gawk at the torture scene, collecting keepsakes and posing for photographs.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] In 1921, the Mexican president Álvaro Obregón along with the former revolutionary general visited Downtown Dallas's Mexican Park in Little Mexico; the small park was on the corner of Akard and Caruth Street, site of the current Fairmont Hotel.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The small neighborhood of Little Mexico was home to a Latin American population that had been drawn to Dallas by factors including the American Dream, better living conditions, and the Mexican Revolution.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Despite the onset of the Great Depression, business in construction was flourishing in 1930.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] That year, Columbus Marion "Dad" Joiner struck oil 100 miles (160 km) east of Dallas in Kilgore, spawning the East Texas oil boom.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Dallas quickly became the financial center for the oil industry in Texas and Oklahoma.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] During World War II, Dallas was a major manufacturing center for military automobiles and aircraft for the United States and Allied forces.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Over 94,000 jeeps and over 6,000 military trucks were produced at the Ford plant in East Dallas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] North American Aviation manufactured over 18,000 aircraft at their plant in Dallas, including the T-6 Texan trainer, P-51 Mustang fighter, and B-24 Liberator bomber.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] On November 22, 1963, United States President John F.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Kennedy was assassinated on Elm Street while his motorcade passed through Dealey Plaza in Downtown Dallas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The upper two floors of the building from which the Warren Commission reported assassin Lee Harvey Oswald shot Kennedy have been converted into a historical museum covering the former president's life and accomplishments.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Kennedy was pronounced dead at Dallas Parkland Memorial Hospital just over 30 minutes after the shooting.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] On July 7, 2016, multiple shots were fired at a Black Lives Matter protest in Downtown Dallas, held against the police killings of two black men from other states.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The gunman, later identified as Micah Xavier Johnson, began firing at police officers at 8:58 p.m., killing five officers and injuring nine.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] This marked the deadliest day for U.S. law enforcement since the September 11 attacks.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Johnson told police during a standoff that he was upset about recent police shootings of black men and wanted to kill whites, especially white officers.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] After hours of negotiation failed, police resorted to a robot-delivered bomb, killing Johnson inside Dallas College El Centro Campus.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The shooting occurred in an area of hotels, restaurants, businesses, and residential apartments only a few blocks away from Dealey Plaza.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Dallas is situated in the Southern United States, in North Texas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] It is the county seat of Dallas County and portions of the city extend into neighboring Collin, Denton, Kaufman, and Rockwall counties.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Many suburbs surround Dallas; three enclaves are within the city boundaries—Cockrell Hill, Highland Park, and University Park.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] According to the United States Census Bureau, the city has a total area of 385.8 square miles (999.3 km2); 340.5 square miles (881.9 km2) of Dallas is land and 45.3 square miles (117.4 km2) of it (11.75%) is water.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Dallas makes up one-fifth of the much larger urbanized area known as the Dallas–Fort Worth metroplex, in which one quarter of all Texans live.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Dallas's skyline has twenty buildings classified as skyscrapers, over 490 feet (150 m) in height.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Despite its tallest building not reaching 980 feet (300 m), Dallas does have a signature building in Bank of America Plaza which is lit up in neon but falls outside the top two hundred tallest buildings in the world.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Although some of Dallas's architecture dates from the late 19th and early 20th centuries, most of the notable architecture in the city is from the modernist and postmodernist eras.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Iconic examples of modernist architecture include Reunion Tower, the John Fitzgerald Kennedy Memorial, I.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Pei's Dallas City Hall and the Morton H.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Good examples of postmodernist skyscrapers are Fountain Place, Bank of America Plaza, Renaissance Tower, JPMorgan Chase Tower, and Comerica Bank Tower.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Downtown Dallas also has residential offerings in downtown, some of which are signature skyline buildings.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Several smaller structures are fashioned in the Gothic Revival style, such as the Kirby Building, and the neoclassical style, as seen in the Davis and Wilson Buildings.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] One architectural "hotbed" in the city is a stretch of historic houses along Swiss Avenue, which has all shades and variants of architecture from Victorian to neoclassical.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The Dallas Downtown Historic District protects a cross-section of Dallas commercial architecture from the 1880s to the 1940s.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The city of Dallas is home to many areas, neighborhoods, and communities.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Dallas can be divided into several geographical areas which include larger geographical sections of territory including many subdivisions or neighborhoods, forming macroneighborhoods.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Central Dallas is anchored by Downtown Dallas, the center of the city, along with Oak Lawn and Uptown, areas characterized by dense retail, restaurants, and nightlife.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Downtown Dallas has a variety of named districts, including the West End Historic District, the Arts District, the Main Street District, Farmers Market District, the City Center Business District, the Convention Center District, and the Reunion District.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] This area includes Uptown, Victory Park, Harwood, Oak Lawn, Dallas Design District, Trinity Groves, Turtle Creek, Cityplace, Knox/Henderson, Greenville, and West Village.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Its historic district has one of the largest collections of Frank Lloyd Wright-inspired prairie-style homes in the United States.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] In the northeast quadrant of the city is Lake Highlands, one of Dallas's most unified middle-class neighborhoods.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Once a separate city founded in the mid-1800s, Oak Cliff was annexed in 1903 by Dallas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] As one of the oldest areas in Dallas, the hilly North Oak Cliff is home to 5 of the 13 conservation districts in Dallas including the architecturally significant Kessler Park neighborhood and trendy Bishop Arts District.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] South Dallas is the location of Cedars, and Fair Park, where the annual State Fair of Texas is held from late September through mid-October.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Also located here is Exposition Park, Dallas, noted for having artists, art galleries, and bars along tree-lined Exposition Avenue.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] South Side Dallas is a popular location for nightly entertainment.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The neighborhood has undergone extensive development and community integration.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] What was once an area characterized by high rates of poverty and crime is now one of the city's most attractive social and living destinations.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Further east, in the southeast quadrant of the city, is the large neighborhood of Pleasant Grove.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Once an independent city, it is a collection of mostly lower-income residential areas stretching to Seagoville in the southeast.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Though a city neighborhood, Pleasant Grove is surrounded by undeveloped land on all sides.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Swampland and wetlands separating it from South Dallas are part of the Great Trinity Forest, a subsection of the city's Trinity River Project, newly appreciated for habitat and flood control.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Dallas and its surrounding area are mostly flat.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The city lies at elevations ranging from 450 to 550 feet (137 to 168 m) above sea level.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The western edge of the Austin Chalk Formation, a limestone escarpment (also known as the "White Rock Escarpment"), rises 230 feet (70 m) and runs roughly north–south through Dallas County.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] South of the Trinity River, the uplift is particularly noticeable in the neighborhoods of Oak Cliff and the adjacent cities of Cockrell Hill, Cedar Hill, Grand Prairie, and Irving.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Marked variations in terrain are also found in cities immediately to the west in Tarrant County surrounding Fort Worth, as well as along Turtle Creek north of Downtown.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Dallas, like many other cities, was founded along a river.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The city was founded at the location of a "white rock crossing" of the Trinity River, where it was easier for wagons to cross the river in the days before ferries or bridges.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The Trinity River, though not usefully navigable, is the major waterway through the city.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] I-35E parallels its path through Dallas along the Stemmons Corridor, then south alongside the western portion of Downtown and past South Dallas and Pleasant Grove, where the river is paralleled by Interstate 45 until it exits the city and heads southeast towards Houston.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The river is flanked on both sides by 50 feet (15 m) tall earthen levees to protect the city from frequent floods.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The project area reaches for over 20 miles (32 km) in length within the city, while the overall geographical land area addressed by the Land Use Plan is approximately 44,000 acres (180 km2) in size—about 20% of the land area in Dallas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Green space along the river encompasses approximately 10,000 acres (40 km2), making it one of the largest and diverse urban parks in the world.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] White Rock Lake and Joe Pool Lake are reservoirs that comprise Dallas's other significant water features.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Built at the beginning of the 20th century, White Rock Lake Park is a popular destination for boaters, rowers, joggers, and bikers, as well as visitors seeking peaceful respite from the city at the 66-acre (267,000 m2) Dallas Arboretum and Botanical Garden, on the lake's eastern shore.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] White Rock Creek feeds into White Rock Lake and then exits into the Trinity River southeast of Downtown Dallas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Trails along White Rock Creek are part of the extensive Dallas County Trails System.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Bachman Lake, just northwest of Love Field Airport, is a smaller lake also popularly used for recreation.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Northeast of the city is Lake Ray Hubbard, a vast 22,745-acre (92 km2) reservoir in an extension of Dallas surrounded by the suburbs of Garland, Rowlett, Rockwall, and Sunnyvale.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] To the west of the city is Mountain Creek Lake, once home to the Naval Air Station Dallas (Hensley Field) and a number of defense aircraft manufacturers.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Dallas has a humid subtropical climate (Köppen climate classification: *Cfa*, Trewartha: *Cfhk*) characteristic of the Southern Plains of the United States.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] It also has both continental and tropical characteristics, characterized by a relatively wide annual temperature range for the latitude.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Located at the lower end of Tornado Alley, it is prone to extreme weather, tornadoes, and hailstorms.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Summers in Dallas are very hot with high humidity, although extended periods of dry weather often occur.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] July and August are typically the hottest months, with an average high of 96.0 °F (36 °C) and an average low of 76.7 °F (25 °C).
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Heat indices regularly surpass 105 °F (41 °C) due to elevated humidity during the summer months, making the summer heat almost unbearable.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The all-time record high is 113 °F (45 °C), set on June 26 and 27, 1980 during the Heat Wave of 1980 at nearby Dallas/Fort Worth International Airport.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Winters in Dallas are usually mild, with occasional cold spells.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The average date of first frost is November 12, and the average date of last frost is March 12.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] January is typically the coldest month, with an average daytime high of 56.8 °F (14 °C) and an average nighttime low of 37.3 °F (3 °C).
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Snow accumulation is seen in the city in about 70% of winter seasons, and snowfall generally occurs 1–2 days out of the year for a seasonal average of 1.5 inches (4 cm).
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Some areas in the region, however, receive more than that, while other areas receive negligible snowfall or none at all.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The all-time record low temperature within the city is −10 °F (−23 °C), set on February 12, 1899, during the Great Blizzard of 1899.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The temperature at nearby Dallas/Fort Worth International Airport reached −2 °F (−19 °C) on February 16, 2021, during the February 2021 North American winter storm.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Spring and autumn are transitional seasons with moderate and pleasant weather.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Vibrant wildflowers (such as the bluebonnet, Indian paintbrush and other flora) bloom in spring and are planted around the highways throughout Texas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Springtime weather can be quite volatile, but temperatures themselves are mild.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Late spring to early summer also tends to be the most humid, with humidity levels frequently exceeding 75%.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The weather in Dallas is also generally pleasant from late September to early December and on many winter days.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Autumn often brings more storms and tornado threats, but they are usually fewer and less severe than in spring.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Each spring, cold fronts moving south from the North collide with warm, humid air streaming in from the Gulf Coast, leading to severe thunderstorms with lightning, torrents of rain, hail, and occasionally, tornadoes.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Over time, tornadoes have probably been the most significant natural threat to the city, as it is near the heart of Tornado Alley.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] A few times each winter in Dallas, warm and humid air from the south will override cold, dry air, resulting in freezing rain or ice and causing disruptions in the city if the roads and highways become slick.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Temperatures reaching 70 °F (21 °C) on average occur on at least four days each winter month.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Dallas averages 26 annual nights at or below freezing, with the winter of 1999–2000 holding the record for the fewest freezing nights with 14.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] During this same span of 15 years, the temperature in the region has only twice dropped below 15 °F (−9 °C), though it will generally fall below 20 °F (−7 °C) in most (67%) years.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Department of Agriculture places Dallas in Plant Hardiness Zone 8b.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] However, mild winter temperatures in the past 15 to 20 years had encouraged the horticulture of more cold-sensitive plants such as *Washingtonia filifera* and *Washingtonia filifera var. robusta* palms, nearly all of which died off during the February 2021 North American winter storm.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] According to the American Lung Association, Dallas has the 12th highest air pollution among U.S. cities, ranking it behind Los Angeles and Houston.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Much of the air pollution in Dallas and the surrounding area comes from a hazardous materials incineration plant in the small town of Midlothian and from cement plants in neighboring Ellis County.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The average daily low in Dallas is 57.4 °F (14 °C), and the average daily high is 76.9 °F (25 °C).
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Dallas receives approximately 39.1 inches (993 mm) of rain per year.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The record snowfall for Dallas was 11.2 inches (28 cm) on February 11, 2010.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Dallas is the ninth-most-populous city in the United States and third in Texas after the cities of Houston and San Antonio.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Its metropolitan area encompasses one-quarter of the population of Texas, and is the largest in the Southern U.S. and Texas followed by the Greater Houston metropolitan area.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] At the 2020 United States census the city of Dallas had 1,304,379 residents, an increase of 106,563 since the 2010 United States census.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Census Bureau estimates that Dallas, in the first years since the 2020 census, lost 4,835 people, leaving the city with a population of 1,299,544.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] There were 524,498 households at the 2020 estimates, up from 2010's 458,057 households, out of which 137,523 had children under the age of 18 living with them.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Approximately 36.2% of households were headed by married couples living together, 57.2% had a single householder male or female with no spouse present, and 35.6% were classified as non-family households with the householder living alone.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] In 2010, 33.7% of all households had one or more people under 18 years of age, and 17.6% had one or more people who were 65 years of age or older.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The average household size in 2020 was 2.52 and the average family size was 3.41.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] In 2018, the owner-occupied housing rate was 40.2% and the renter-occupied housing rate was 59.8%.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] At the 2010 census, the city's age distribution of the population showed 26.5% under the age of 18 and 8.8% who were 65 years of age or older.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] In 2010, 50.0% of the population was male and 50.0% was female.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] In 2020, the median age 32.9 years; for every 100 females, there were 98.4 males.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] According to the 2020 American Community Survey, the median income for a household in the city was $54,747; families had a median household income of $60,895; married-couple families $81,761; and non-families $45,658.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] In 2003–2007's survey, male full-time workers had a median income of $32,265 versus $32,402 for female full-time workers.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The per capita income for the city was $25,904.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] About 18.7% of families and 21.7% of the population were below the poverty line, including 33.6% of those under age 18 and 13.4% of those aged 65 or over.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Per 2007's survey, the median price for a house was $129,600; by 2020, the median price for a house was valued at $252,300, with 54.4% of owner-occupied units from $50,000 to $299,999.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The 2022 Point-In-Time Homeless Count found there were 4,410 homeless people in Dallas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The region surrounding Dallas is a habitat for mosquitoes, creating a pest problem for humans.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Dallas and the surrounding area is sprayed regularly to control mosquito-borne diseases such as West Nile virus.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Dallas's population was historically predominantly White (non-Hispanic Whites made up 82.8% of the population in 1930), but its population has diversified due to immigration and white flight over the 20th century.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Since then, the non-Hispanic White population has declined to less than one-third of the city's population.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Census Bureau's 2019 estimates, 29.1% were non-Hispanic White 24.3% Black and African American, 0.3% American Indian or Alaska Native, 3.7% Asian, and 1.4% from two or more races.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Native Hawaiian and other Pacific Islanders made up a total of 312 residents according to 2019's census estimates, down from 606 in 2017.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Hispanic or Latino Americans of any race made up 41.2% of the estimated population in 2019.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Among the Hispanic or Latino American population in 2019, 34.6% of Dallas was Mexican, 0.4% Puerto Rican, 0.2% Cuban and 6.0% other Hispanic or Latino American.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] In 2017's American Community Survey estimates among the demographic 35.5% were Mexican, 0.6% Puerto Rican, 0.4% Cuban, and 5.4% other Hispanic or Latino.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] By 2020, Hispanic or Latino Americans of any race continued to constitute the largest ethnic group in the city proper, reflecting nationwide demographic trends.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The Dallas area is a major living destination for Mexican Americans and other Hispanic and Latino American immigrants.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The southwestern portion of the city, particularly Oak Cliff is chiefly inhabited by Hispanic and Latino American residents.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The southeastern portion of the city Pleasant Grove is chiefly inhabited by African American and Hispanic or Latino American residents, while the southern portion of the city is predominantly black.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The west and east sides of the city are predominantly Hispanic or Latino American; Garland also has a large Spanish-speaking population.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] North Dallas has many enclaves of predominantly white, black and especially Hispanic or Latino American residents.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The Dallas area is also a major living destination for Black and African Americans primarily due to its strong and diverse economy.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Between 2010 and 2020, the Dallas area had the second-most new Black and African American residents only behind the Atlanta area and slightly above the Houston area.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The notable influx of African Americans is partly due to the New Great Migration.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] There is a significant number of people from the Horn of Africa, immigrants from Ethiopia, Eritrea and Somalia.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The Dallas–Fort-Worth metroplex had an estimated 70,000 Russian-speakers (as of November 6, 2012) mostly immigrants from the former Soviet Bloc.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Included in this population are Russians, Russian Jews, Ukrainians, Armenians, Belarusians, Moldavians Uzbek, Kirghiz, and others.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The Russian-speaking population of Dallas has continued to grow in the sector of "American husbands-Russian wives".
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Russian DFW has its own newspaper, *The Dallas Telegraph*.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] In addition, Dallas and its suburbs are home to a large number of Asian Americans including those of Indian, Vietnamese, Chinese, Korean, Filipino, Japanese, and other heritage.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Among large-sized cities in the United States, Plano, the northern suburb of Dallas, has the 6th largest Chinese American population as of 2016.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The Plano-Richardson area in particular had an estimated 30,000 Iranian Americans in 2012.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] With so many immigrant groups, there are often multilingual signs in the linguistic landscape.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Census Bureau data released in December 2013, 23 percent of Dallas County residents were foreign-born, while 16 percent of Tarrant County residents were foreign-born.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The 2018 census estimates determined that the city of Dallas's foreign-born population consisted of 25.4% naturalized citizens and 74.6% non-citizens.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Dallas and the Metroplex have one of the largest lesbian, gay, bisexual, and transgender (LGBT) populations in the country.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Throughout the year there are LGBT events held in the area, including the annual Alan Ross Texas Freedom (Pride) Parade and Festival in June, which draws approximately 50,000 attendees.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] For decades, the Oak Lawn and Bishop Arts districts have been known as the epicenters of LGBT culture in Dallas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Christianity is the most prevalently practiced religion in Dallas and the wider metropolitan area according to a 2014 study by the Pew Research Center (78%), and the Public Religion Research Institute's 2020 study (77%).
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] There is a large Protestant Christian influence in the Dallas community, though the city of Dallas and Dallas County have more Catholic than Protestant residents, while the reverse is usually true for the suburban areas of Dallas and the city of Fort Worth.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Dallas has been called the "Prison Ministry Capital of the World" by the prison ministry community.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] It is a home for the International Network of Prison Ministries, the Coalition of Prison Evangelists, Bill Glass Champions for Life, Chaplain Ray's International Prison Ministry, and 60 other prison ministries.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Methodist, Baptist, and Presbyterian churches are prominent in many neighborhoods and anchor two of the city's major private universities (Southern Methodist University and Dallas Baptist University).
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Dallas is also home to two evangelical seminaries: the Dallas Theological Seminary and Criswell College.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Many Bible schools including Christ For The Nations Institute are also headquartered in the city.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The Christian creationist apologetics group Institute for Creation Research is headquartered in Dallas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] According to the Pew Research Center, evangelical Protestantism constituted the largest form of Protestantism in the area as of 2014.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The largest single evangelical Protestant group were Baptists.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The largest Baptist denomination was the Southern Baptist Convention, followed by the historically black National Baptist Convention USA.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] African-initiated Protestant churches including Ethiopian Evangelical churches can be found throughout the metropolitan area.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The Catholic Church is also a significant religious organization in the Dallas area and operates the University of Dallas, a liberal-arts university in the Dallas suburb of Irving.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The Cathedral Santuario de la Virgen de Guadalupe in the Arts District is home to the second-largest Catholic church membership in the United States and overseas, consisting over 70 parishes in the Dallas Diocese.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The Society of Jesus operates the Jesuit College Preparatory School of Dallas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Dallas is also home to numerous Eastern Orthodox and Oriental Orthodox churches including Saint Seraphim Cathedral, see of the Orthodox Church in America's Southern Diocese.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The Greek Orthodox Archdiocese of America (Ecumenical Patriarchate) has one parish in the city of Dallas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Sarkis Armenian Church (serving as part of the Armenian Apostolic Church facility).
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Jehovah's Witnesses has a large number of members throughout the Dallas metropolitan division.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] In addition, there are several Unitarian Universalist congregations, including First Unitarian Church of Dallas, founded in 1899.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] A large community of the United Church of Christ exists in the city.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The most prominent UCC-affiliated church is the Cathedral of Hope, a predominantly LGBT-affirming church.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints has a sizeable community in the Dallas-Fort Worth Metroplex.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Members in the area are organized into 24 stakes.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The Dallas Texas Temple, dedicated in 1984 as the first temple in Texas, is located in the city.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Two more temples, the Fort Worth Texas Temple and Fairview Texas Temple, are under construction in the area.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Since the establishment of the city's first Jewish cemetery in 1854 and its first congregation (which would eventually be known as Temple Emanu-El) in 1873, Dallasite Jews have been well represented among leaders in commerce, politics, and various professional fields in Dallas and elsewhere.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Furthermore, a large Muslim community exists in the north and northeastern portions of Dallas, as well as in the northern Dallas suburbs.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] The oldest mosque in Dallas is Masjid Al-Islam just south of Downtown.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Immigrants from East Asia, Southeast Asia, Nepal, and Sri Lanka have all contributed to the Buddhist population, which is concentrated in the northern suburbs of Garland, Plano and Richardson.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Numerous Buddhist temples dot the Metroplex including The Buddhist Center of Dallas, Lien Hoa Vietnamese Temple of Irving, and Kadampa Meditation Center Texas and Wat Buddhamahamunee of Arlington.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] A large and growing Hindu Community lives in the Dallas–Fort Worth metroplex.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Most live in Collin County and the northern portions of Dallas County.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Over 28 Hindu Temples exist in the area.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Some notable ones include the DFW Hindu Temple, the North Texas Hindu Mandir, Radha Krishna Temple, Dallas and Karya Siddhi Hanuman Temple.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] There are also at least three Sikh Gurudwaras in this metropolitan area.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] For irreligious people, the Winter Solstice Celebration is held in the Metroplex although some of its participants are also neo-pagans and New Agers.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] According to the FBI, a city to city comparison of crime rates can be misleading, because recording practices vary from city to city, citizens report different percentages of crimes from one city to the next, and the actual number of people physically present in a city is unknown.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] With that in mind, Dallas has one of the top 10 crime rates in Texas and its crime rate is higher than the national average.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Since 2020, Dallas's murder rate has seen a notable increase.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] In 2020, Dallas recorded 251 murders which was a 20-year high.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] By 2022 it decreased to 214 but then increased to 246 in 2023.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] As of 2020, the gang presence in Dallas has grown significantly and is heavily responsible for the spike in crime.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p01] Dallas leaders have made crime reduction a major priority.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] In its beginnings, Dallas relied on farming, neighboring Fort Worth's Stockyards, and its prime location on Native American trade routes to sustain itself.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Dallas's key to growth came in 1873 with the construction of multiple rail lines through the city.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] As Dallas grew and technology developed, cotton became its boon and by 1900, Dallas was the largest inland cotton market in the world, becoming a leader in cotton gin machinery manufacturing.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] By the early 1900s, Dallas was a hub for economic activity all over the Southern United States and was selected in 1914 as the seat of the Eleventh Federal Reserve District.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] By 1925, Texas churned out more than 1⁄3 of the nation's cotton crop, with 31% of Texas cotton produced within a 100-mile (160 km) radius of Dallas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] In the 1930s, petroleum was discovered east of Dallas, near Kilgore.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Dallas's proximity to the discovery put it immediately at the center of the nation's petroleum market.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Petroleum discoveries in the Permian Basin, the Panhandle, the Gulf Coast, and Oklahoma in the following years further solidified Dallas's position as the hub of the market.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The end of World War II left Dallas seeded with a nexus of communications, engineering, and production talent by companies such as Collins Radio Corporation.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Decades later, the telecommunications and information revolutions still drive a large portion of the local economy.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The city is sometimes referred to as the heart of "Silicon Prairie" because of a high concentration of telecommunications companies in the region, the epicenter of which lies along the Telecom Corridor in Richardson, a northern suburb of Dallas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Texas Instruments, a major manufacturer, employs 10,400 people at its corporate headquarters and chip plants in Dallas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] In the 1980s Dallas was a real estate hotbed, with the increasing metropolitan population bringing with it a demand for new housing and office space.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Several of Downtown Dallas's largest buildings are the fruit of this boom, but over-speculation, the savings and loan crisis and an oil bust brought the 1980s building boom to an end for Dallas as well as its sister city Houston.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Between the late 1980s and the early 2000s, central Dallas went through a slow period of growth.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] However, since the early 2000s the central core of Dallas has been enjoying steady and significant growth encompassing both repurposing of older commercial buildings in Downtown Dallas into residential and hotel uses, as well as the construction of new office and residential towers.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The opening of Klyde Warren Park, built across Woodall Rodgers Freeway seamlessly connecting the central Dallas CBD to Uptown/Victory Park, has acted synergistically with the highly successful Dallas Arts District, so both have become catalysts for significant new development in central Dallas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The residential real estate market in the Dallas–Fort Worth metroplex has not only been resilient but has once again returned to a boom status.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Dallas and the greater metro area have been leading the nation in apartment construction and net leasing, with rents reaching all-time highs.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Single family home sales, whether pre-owned or new construction, along with home price appreciation, were leading the nation since 2015.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] A sudden drop in the price of oil, starting in mid-2014 and accelerating throughout 2015, has not significantly affected Dallas and its greater metro area due to the highly diversified nature of its economy.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Dallas and the metropolitan region continue to see strong demand for housing, apartment and office leasing, shopping center space, warehouse and industrial space with overall job growth remaining very robust.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Oil-dependent cities and regions have felt significant effects from the downturn, but Dallas's growth has continued unabated, strengthening in 2015.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The Dallas–Fort Worth area has one of the largest concentrations of corporate headquarters for publicly traded companies in the United States.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] *Fortune Magazine*'s 2022 annual list of the Fortune 500 in America indicates the city of Dallas had 11 Fortune 500 companies and the DFW region as a whole had 23.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] As of 2022, Dallas–Fort Worth represents the second-largest concentration of Fortune 500 headquarters in Texas and fourth-largest in the United States, behind the metropolitan areas of Houston (24), Chicago (35) and New York (62).
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] In 2008, AT&T relocated their headquarters to Downtown Dallas; AT&T is the largest telecommunications company in the world and was the ninth largest company in the nation by revenue for 2017.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] In October 2016, Jacobs Engineering, one of the world's largest engineering companies, relocated from Pasadena, California to Downtown Dallas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Nearby Irving is home to six Fortune 500 companies of its own, including McKesson, the country's largest pharmaceutical distributor and listed at number seven overall on the 2021 Fortune 500 list, Fluor (engineering), Kimberly-Clark, Celanese, Michaels Companies, and Vistra Energy.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Plano is home to an additional four Fortune 500 companies, including J.C.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Penney, Alliance Data Systems, Yum China, and Dr.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Fort Worth is home to two Fortune 500 companies, including American Airlines, the largest airline in the world by revenue, fleet size, profit, passengers carried and revenue passenger mile and D.R.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Horton, the largest homebuilder in America.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Westlake, TX, north of Fort Worth, now has two Fortune 500 companies: Financial services giant, Charles Schwab, and convenience store distributor, Core-Mark.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] One Fortune 500 company, GameStop, is based in Grapevine.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Cheese's, Zale Corporation, and Fossil, Inc.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Many of these companies—and others throughout the DFW metroplex—comprise the Dallas Regional Chamber.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Komen for the Cure, the world's largest breast cancer organization, was founded and is headquartered in Dallas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] In addition to its large number of businesses, Dallas has more shopping centers per capita than any other city in the United States and is also home to the second shopping center ever built in the United States, Highland Park Village, which opened in 1931.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Dallas is home of the two other major malls in North Texas, the Dallas Galleria and NorthPark Center, which is the second largest mall in Texas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Both malls feature high-end stores and are major tourist draws for the region.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Tourism is an important sector of Dallas's economy and is its tenth largest employer, providing 56,000 jobs.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Dallas receives on average 25 million visitors annually.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The Arts District in the northern section of Downtown is home to several arts venues and is the largest contiguous arts district in the United States.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Notable venues in the district include the Dallas Museum of Art; the Morton H.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Meyerson Symphony Center, home to the Dallas Symphony Orchestra and Dallas Wind Symphony; the Nasher Sculpture Center; and the Trammell & Margaret Crow Collection of Asian Art.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The Perot Museum of Nature and Science, also in Downtown Dallas, is a natural history and science museum.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Designed by 2005 Pritzker Architecture Prize Laureate Thom Mayne and his firm Morphosis Architects, the 180,000-square-foot (17,000 m2) facility has six floors and stands about 14 stories high.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Not far north of the area is the Meadows Museum at Southern Methodist University.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] In 2009, it joined up with Madrid's Prado Museum for a three-year partnership.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The Prado focuses on Spanish visual art and has a collection of Spanish art in North America, with works by de Juanes, El Greco, Fortuny, Goya, Murillo, Picasso, Pkensa, Ribera, Rico, Velasquez, Zurbaran, and other Spaniards.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] These works, as well as non-Spanish highlights like sculptures by Rodin and Moore, have been so successful of a collaboration that the Prado and Meadows have agreed upon an extension of the partnership.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The former Texas School Book Depository, from which, according to the Warren Commission Report, Lee Harvey Oswald shot and killed President John F.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Kennedy in 1963, has served since the 1980s as a county government office building, except for its sixth and seventh floors, which house the Sixth Floor Museum.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The American Museum of the Miniature Arts is at the Hall of State in Fair Park.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The Arts District is also home to DISD's Booker T.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Washington High School for the Performing and Visual Arts, a magnet school that was recently expanded.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] City Center District, next to the Arts District, is home to the Dallas Contemporary.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The Institute for Creation Research operates the ICR Discovery Center for Science & Earth History, a creationism museum, in Dallas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Deep Ellum, immediately east of Downtown, originally became popular during the 1920s and 1930s as the prime jazz and blues hot spot in the South.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Artists such as Blind Lemon Jefferson, Robert Johnson, Huddie "Lead Belly" Ledbetter, and Bessie Smith played in original Deep Ellum clubs such as the Harlem and the Palace.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Today, Deep Ellum is home to hundreds of artists who live in lofts or operate in studios throughout the district alongside bars, pubs, and concert venues.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] A major art infusion in the area results from the city's lax stance on graffiti, and a number of public spaces, including tunnels, sides of buildings, sidewalks, and streets, are covered in murals.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] One major example, the Good-Latimer tunnel, was torn down in late 2006 to accommodate the construction of a light rail line through the site.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Like Deep Ellum before it, the Cedars neighborhood to the south of Downtown has also seen a growing population of studio artists and an expanding roster of entertainment venues.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The area's art scene began to grow in the early 2000s with the opening of Southside on Lamar, an old Sears Roebuck and Company warehouse converted into lofts, studios, and retail.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Current attractions include Gilley's Dallas and Poor David's Pub.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Dallas Mavericks owner and local entrepreneur Mark Cuban purchased land along Lamar Street near Cedars Station in September 2005, and locals speculate he is planning an entertainment complex for the site.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] South of the Trinity River, the Bishop Arts District in Oak Cliff is home to a number of studio artists living in converted warehouses.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Walls of buildings along alleyways and streets are painted with murals, and the surrounding streets contain many eclectic restaurants and shops.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Dallas has an Office of Cultural Affairs as a department of the city government.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The office is responsible for six cultural centers throughout the city, funding for local artists and theaters, initiating public art projects, and running the city-owned classical radio station WRR.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The Los Angeles-class submarine USS *Dallas* was planned to become a museum ship near the Trinity River after her decommissioning in September 2014, but this has since been delayed.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] It will be taken apart into massive sections in Houston and be transported by trucks to the museum site and will be put back together.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The city is served by the Dallas Public Library system.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The system was created by the Dallas Federation of Women's Clubs with efforts spearheaded by then president May Dickson Exall.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Her fundraising efforts led to a grant from philanthropist and steel baron Andrew Carnegie, which allowed the library system to build its first branch in 1901.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Today, the library operates 30 branch locations throughout the city, including the 8-story J.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Erik Jonsson Central Library in the Government District of Downtown.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Dallas is known for its barbecue, authentic Mexican, and Tex-Mex cuisine.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Famous products of the Dallas culinary scene include the Frozen margarita machine by restaurateur Mariano Martinez in 1971.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The State Fair of Texas has been held annually at Fair Park since 1886, and generates an estimated $50 million to the city's economy annually.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The Red River Shootout, a football game that pits the University of Texas at Austin against the University of Oklahoma at the Cotton Bowl, also brings significant crowds to the city.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The city also hosts the State Fair Classic and Heart of Dallas Bowl at the Cotton Bowl.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] With the opening of Victory Park, WFAA began hosting an annual New Year's Eve celebration in AT&T Plaza that the television station hoped would be reminiscent of celebrations in New York's Times Square; New Year's Eve 2011 set a new record of 32,000 people in attendance.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] After the discontinuance of the "Big D NYE" festivities a few years later, a new end-of-year event was started downtown, with a big fireworks show put on at Reunion Tower, which has since aired on KXAS and other TV stations around the state and region.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Also, several Omni hotels in the Dallas area host large events to welcome in the new year, including murder mystery parties, rave-inspired events, and other events.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Downtown Dallas is home to two major league sports teams that play at the American Airlines Center: the Dallas Mavericks (NBA), who won the NBA Championship in 2011, and the Dallas Stars (NHL), who won the Stanley Cup in 1999.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Nearby Arlington is home to the Dallas Cowboys (NFL), who play at the AT&T Stadium and have won five Super Bowls, the Texas Rangers (MLB), who play at Globe Life Field and won the World Series in 2023, and the Dallas Wings (WNBA), who play at College Park Center.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] MLS team FC Dallas plays at Toyota Stadium in Frisco and won the Lamar Hunt U.S.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The newest team in Dallas is Dallas Trinity FC, the first professional women's soccer team that plays at the historic Cotton Bowl (stadium).
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The city is home to several minor league and college sports programs in the area.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Since joining the league as an expansion team in 1960, the Cowboys have enjoyed substantial success, advancing to eight Super Bowls and winning five.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The Cowboys are financially the most valuable sports franchise in the world, worth approximately $4 billion.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] In 2009, they relocated to their new 80,000-seat stadium in Arlington, which was the site of Super Bowl XLV and is set to host the most matches during the 2026 FIFA World Cup.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The Cowboys are currently part of the East Division of the National Football Conference (NFC).
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The Texas Rangers won the American League pennant in 2010, 2011 and 2023, and won the World Series in 2023.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The franchise relocated from Washington D.C. in 1972.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] They play in the West Division of the American League.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The Dallas Mavericks joined the league as an expansion team in 1980.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] They won their first National Basketball Association championship in 2011 led by Dirk Nowitzki.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] They play in the Southwest Division of the Western Conference.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The Dallas Stars moved to North Texas in 1993 as a relocation from the former team, the Minnesota North Stars.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The Stars have won eight division titles in Dallas, two Presidents' Trophies as the top regular season team in the NHL, the Western Conference championship three times, and in 1998–99, the Stanley Cup.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The team plays in the Central Division of the Western Conference.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] FC Dallas play at Toyota Stadium (formerly FC Dallas Stadium and Pizza Hut Park), a stadium that opened in 2005.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] They currently play in MLS's Western Conference.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The team was originally called the Dallas Burn and used to play in the Cotton Bowl.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Although FC Dallas has not yet won a MLS Cup, they won the Lamar Hunt U.S.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Open Cup in 1997 and 2016 and the Supporters' Shield in 2016.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Previously, the Dallas Tornado played in the North American Soccer League from 1968 to 1981.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The Dallas Wings came to The Metroplex in 2016 after relocating from Tulsa.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] There are many notable minor league teams in the Dallas-Fort Worth.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The Allen Americans are a professional ice hockey team headquartered at the Credit Union of Texas Event Center in Allen, Texas, which currently plays in the ECHL.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] They are the minor league affiliate of the NHL's Seattle Kraken.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The team was founded in 2009 in the Central Hockey League(CHL).
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The Dallas Renegades are a professional football team in the UFL that plays their home games at Toyota Stadium.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The Dallas Sidekicks (2012) are an American professional indoor soccer team based in Allen, Texas, a suburb of Dallas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] They play their home games in the Credit Union of Texas Event Center.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The team is named after the original Dallas Sidekicks that operated from 1984 to 2004.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The MLS-affiliated North Texas SC team is a member of MLS Next Pro and plays in Frisco at Toyota Stadium; it is the reserve team of FC Dallas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The Dallas Mavericks own an NBA G League team, the Texas Legends.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Rugby is a developing sport in Dallas and Texas in general.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The multiple clubs, ranging from men's and women's clubs to collegiate and high school, are part of the Texas Rugby Football Union.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Dallas was one of only 16 cities in the United States included in the Rugby Super League, represented by Dallas Harlequins.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Australian rules football is also growing in Dallas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The Dallas Magpies, founded in 1998, compete in the United States Australian Football League.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The only Division I sports program within the Dallas political boundary is the Dallas Baptist University Patriots baseball team.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Although outside the city limits, the Mustangs of Southern Methodist University are in the enclave of University Park.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Neighboring cities Fort Worth, Arlington, and Denton are home to the Texas Christian University Horned Frogs, UT Arlington Mavericks, and University of North Texas Mean Green respectively.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The Dallas area hosted the Final Four of the 2014 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament at AT&T Stadium.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The college Cotton Bowl Classic football game was played at the Cotton Bowl through its 2009 game, but has moved to AT&T Stadium.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The Red River Showdown is an American college football rivalry game played annually at the Cotton Bowl Stadium during the second weekend of the State Fair of Texas in October.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The game is played by the Oklahoma Sooners football team of the University of Oklahoma and the Texas Longhorns football team of the University of Texas at Austin.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The 10,000-capacity Forester Stadium, which is used mainly for football and soccer, is also located in Dallas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Dallas Trinity FC is the first professional women's soccer team in Dallas that plays at the historic Cotton Bowl (stadium) located in Downtown Dallas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Originally founded in May 2023 by the Neil family and managed by Chris Petrucelli, the club kicked off its inaugural season in August 2024 when they played Tampa Bay Sun FC, ending in a 1 v 1 tie.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Following this match was two very significant matches for the club, the friendly match and home opener.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The club played their friendly match vs FC Barcelona Femení where they lost 0-6 and the club's official home match was against DC Power FC where they tied 1-1.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The club finished the season 12–9–7, finishing third and getting eliminated by Tampa Bay Sun FC by the final score of 2–1 in the semi-finals of the USL Championship.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Following its inaugural season, the teams parted ways with Pauline MacDonald and Gavin Beith.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Recently, the team announced its State Fair Clasico Match during the Texas State Fair at Fair Park on October 18 vs Club América Femenil.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Major League Volleyball expanded to the Dallas market after announcing plans for a single, unified professional women's volleyball league with the former Pro Volleyball Federation (PVF) in 2025.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The Dallas franchise of Major League Volleyball was officially named Dallas Pulse and confirmed Comerica Center in Frisco as its home court for their 2026 debut.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] In their inaugural season, the Pulse have clinched a postseason spot with Head Coach, Shannon Winzer, as they prepare to host the 2026 MLV Championship at Comerica Center.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Dallas maintains and operates 406 parks on 21,000 acres (85 km2) of parkland.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The city's parks contain 17 separate lakes, including White Rock and Bachman lakes, spanning a total of 4,400 acres (17.81 km2).
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Built in 1936 for the Texas Centennial Exposition world's fair, Fair Park is the world's largest collection of Art Deco exhibit buildings, art, and sculptures; Fair Park is also home to the State Fair of Texas, the largest state fair in the United States with 2 million visitors.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] In November 2019, consultants presented to the public a master plan to revitalize the area.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Named after Klyde Warren, the young son of billionaire Kelcy Warren, the 5.2-acre Klyde Warren Park was built above Woodall Rodgers Freeway and connects Uptown and Downtown, specifically the Arts District.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Klyde Warren Park is home to an amphitheater, jogging trails, a children's park, a dog park, a putting green, croquet, ping pong, chess, an outdoor library, and two restaurants.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Food trucks give another option of dining and are lined along the park's Downtown side.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] There are also weekly planned events, including yoga, Zumba, skyline tours, tai chi, and meditation.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Klyde Warren Park is home to a free trolley stop on Olive St., which riders can connect to Downtown, McKinney Avenue, and West Village.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Built in 1913, Turtle Creek Parkway park is a 23.7-acre (9.6 ha) linear park in between Turtle Creek and Turtle Creek Boulevard in the aptly named Turtle Creek neighborhood.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Archaeological surveys discovered dart points and flint chips dating 3,000 years to 1,000 BCE.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] This site was later discovered to be home to Native Americans who cherished the trees and natural spring water.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The park is across Turtle Creek from Kalita Humphreys Theater, designed by Frank Lloyd Wright.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Opened on July 4, 1906, Lake Cliff Park was called "the Southwest's Greatest Playground".
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The park was home to an amusement park, a large pool, waterslides, the world's largest skating rink, and three theaters, the largest being the 2,500-seat Casino Theater.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] After the streetcar bridge that brought most of the park visitors collapsed, Lake Cliff Park was sold.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The Casino Theater moved and the pool was demolished after a polio scare in 1959.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The pool was Dallas's first municipal pool.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] In 1935, Dallas purchased 36 acres (15 ha) from John Cole's estate to develop Reverchon Park.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Reverchon Park was named after botanist Julien Reverchon, who left France to live in the La Reunion colony, which was founded in the mid-1800s and was situated in present-day West Dallas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Reverchon Park was planned to be the crown jewel of the Dallas park system and was even referred to as the "Central Park" of Dallas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Improvements were made throughout the years, including the Iris Bowl, picnic settings, a baseball diamond, and tennis courts.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The Iris Bowl celebrated many Greek pageants, dances, and other performances.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The Gill Well was installed for nearby residents and drew people all across Texas who wanted to experience the water's healing powers.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The baseball diamond was host to a 1953 exhibition game for the New York Giants and the Cleveland Indians.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] As part of the ongoing Trinity River Project, the Great Trinity Forest, at 6,000 acres (24 km2), is the largest urban hardwood forest in the United States and is part of the largest urban park in the United States.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The Trinity River Audubon Center is a new addition to the park.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Opened in 2008, it serves as a gateway to many trails and other nature-viewing activities in the area.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The Trinity River Audubon Center is the first LEED-certified building built by the City of Dallas Parks and Recreation Department.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Named after its former railroad name, the Missouri-Kansas-Texas Railroad (or "MKT" Railroad), the 3.5-mile (5.6 km) stretch of railroad was purchased by the city of Dallas and transformed into the city's premier trail.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Stretching from Victory Park, the 30-acre (12 ha) Katy Trail passes through the Turtle Creek and Knox Park neighborhoods and runs along the east side of Highland Park.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The trail ends at Central Expressway, but extensions are underway to extend the trail to the White Rock Lake Trail in Lakewood.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Dallas hosts three of the twenty-one preserves of the extensive 3,200 acres (13 km2) Dallas County Preserve System.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The Joppa Preserve, the McCommas Bluff Preserve, and the Cedar Ridge Preserve are within the Dallas city limits.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The Cedar Ridge Preserve was known as the Dallas Nature Center, but the Audubon Dallas group now manages the 633-acre (2.56 km2) natural habitat park on behalf of the city of Dallas and Dallas County.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The preserve sits at an elevation of 755 feet (230 m) above sea level and offers a variety of outdoor activities, including 10 miles (16 km) of hiking trails and picnic areas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The city is also home to Texas's first and largest zoo, the 106-acre (0.43 km2) Dallas Zoo, which opened at its current location in 1888.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The city uses a council-manager government, with Eric Johnson serving as mayor, Kimberly Tolbert serving as city manager, and 14 council members serving as representatives to the 14 council districts in the city.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] This organizational structure was contested by some in favor of a strong-mayor city charter, only to be rejected by Dallas voters.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Martínez become the first Latin American to sit as a councilwoman in Dallas's city council.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] In the 2017–2018 fiscal year, the city's total budget (the sum of operating and capital budgets) was $3.3 billion.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The United States District Court for the Northern District of Texas, which exercises original jurisdiction over 100 counties in North and West Texas, convenes in the Earle Cabell Federal Building and Courthouse in the Government District of Downtown.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The same building additionally houses United States Bankruptcy and Magistrate Courts and a United States Attorney office.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Dallas also is the seat of the Fifth Court of Appeals of Texas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Since 2023, Dallas has been the largest city in the United States with a Republican mayor after Eric Johnson switched parties after winning re-election.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Democratic voters dominate the majority of the city, especially the central urban core and southern sectors, with Republicans spreading a sliver of suburban neighborhoods in North Dallas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] In the 2004 U.S. presidential election, 57% of voters in Dallas's city limits voted for John Kerry over George W.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Dallas County was closely divided, with 50% of voters voting for Bush and 49% voting for Kerry.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Results in the 2008 and 2012 elections favored Barack Obama, with the 44th President receiving 57% of Dallas County voters in both years, with greater margins in the city of Dallas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] In the 2016 U.S. presidential election, approximately 66% of Dallas voters voted for Hillary Clinton, with 28% of city voters voting for Donald Trump.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Dallas County as a whole saw 61% of voters voting for Clinton, with 35% support for Trump.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] In 2004, Lupe Valdez was elected Dallas County Sheriff.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] An open lesbian, Valdez was the only female sheriff in the state of Texas until her resignation.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Despite controversies in her handling of county jails, she won re-election in 2008 with a 10-point victory over Republican challenger Lowell Cannaday.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] In the 2024 United States presidential election, Donald Trump, achieved 34.1% of the vote in the city of Dallas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] This marked the highest level of support for a Republican candidate in the city since the 2012 election, when Mitt Romney received a comparable percentage.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Trump's performance in Dallas has been attributed in part to a notable shift in Hispanic voter preferences within Texas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Trump garnered an estimated 55% of the Hispanic vote statewide, a significant improvement from his performance among Hispanic voters in 2016.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] There are 337 public schools, 89 private schools, 38 colleges, and 32 libraries in Dallas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Dallas–Fort Worth is also home to six Nobel Laureates.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The Dallas area has a high number of colleges and universities.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] In addition to those in the city, the surrounding cities also have a number of universities, colleges, trade schools, and other educational institutions.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The Texas Legislature defines all areas in Dallas County and in the Carrollton-Farmers Branch Independent School District as being in the service area of Dallas College (formerly Dallas County Community College District or DCCCD).
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Areas in Collin County are assigned to Collin College.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Most areas in the city of Dallas are within the Dallas Independent School District, the 12th-largest school district in the United States and second largest in Texas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The school district operates independently of the city and enrolls over 161,000 students.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] As of 2003 DISD has the majority of K–12 students in the city of Dallas, and a proportionately larger number of students who are not non-Hispanic white.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] A few areas of Dallas also extend into other school districts in Dallas County, including Carrollton-Farmers Branch, Coppell, Duncanville, Garland, Highland Park, Irving, Mesquite, and Richardson.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Portions of Dallas in Collin County are in Plano ISD, and portions of Dallas in Denton County are in the Carrollton-Farmers Branch ISD.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The Wilmer-Hutchins Independent School District once served portions of southern Dallas, but it was shut down for the 2005–2006 year.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] WHISD students started attending other Dallas ISD schools during that time.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Following the close, the Texas Education Agency consolidated WHISD into Dallas ISD.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] In 2003 Royce Hanson, author of *Civic Culture and Urban Change: Governing Dallas*, stated that the Plano, Richardson, and Wilmer-Hutchins school districts were the "most significant" of the public school students with students in Dallas who were not in Dallas ISD.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Many school districts in Dallas County, including Dallas ISD, were formerly served by a governmental agency called Dallas County Schools.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] The system provided busing and other transportation services, access to a massive media library, technology services, strong ties to local organizations for education/community integration, and staff development programs.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p02] Students from Dallas attend many private schools in Dallas, and in nearby areas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] Dallas has several local newspapers, magazines, television stations and radio stations that serve the Dallas–Fort Worth metroplex, which is the fifth-largest media market in the United States.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] Dallas has one major daily newspaper, *The Dallas Morning News*, which was founded in 1885 by A.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] The *Dallas Times Herald*, started in 1888, was the *Morning News'* major competitor until Belo purchased it on December 8, 1991, and closed the paper down the next day.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] Other daily newspapers are *Al Día*, a Spanish-language paper published by Belo, and a number of ethnic newspapers printed in languages such as Chinese, Korean, and Vietnamese.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] Other publications include the *Dallas Weekly* and the *Elite News*, all weekly news publications.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] The *Dallas Observer* and the *North Texas Journal* are also alternative weekly newspapers.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] *The Dallas Morning News* formerly had a weekly publication, *Neighborsgo*, which came out every Friday and focused on community news.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] Readers could post stories and contribute content to the website.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] In terms of the larger metro area, the *Fort Worth Star-Telegram* is another major daily newspaper, covering Fort Worth's metropolitan division.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] It also publishes a major Spanish-language newspaper for the entire metro area known as *La Estrella*.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] To the north of Dallas and Fort Worth, the *Denton Record-Chronicle* primarily covers news for the city of Denton and Denton County.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] KTXA 21 and KFAA 29 are an independent stations; KTXA was previously affiliated with the now-defunct UPN network.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] Over 101 radio stations operate within range of Dallas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] The city of Dallas operates WRR 101.1 FM, the area's main classical music station, from city offices in Fair Park.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] Its original sister station, licensed as WRR in 1921, is the oldest commercially operated radio station in Texas and claims to be the second-oldest in the United States, after KDKA in Pittsburgh.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] KKDA-FM (K104), an urban contemporary station, and KRNB (Smooth R&B 105.7), an urban adult contemporary station, are owned independently by Service Broadcasting Corporation.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] Slavic Voice of America media group serves Russian-speaking Americans out of Dallas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] Hispanic Broadcasting Corporation (HBC), the largest company in the Spanish-language radio station business, is based in Dallas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] In 2003, HBC was acquired by Univision and became Univision Radio Inc., but the radio company remains headquartered in the city.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] The Dallas Police Department provides most policing in Dallas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] The Dallas Chief of Police is Daniel Comeaux.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] The police headquarters are in the Cedars neighborhood of southern Dallas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] Emergency medical services and fire protection in the city are provided by the Dallas Fire-Rescue Department.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] The Dallas Fire & Rescue chief is Dominique Artis.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] The department operates the Dallas Firefighter's Museum built in 1907 along Parry Avenue near Fair Park.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] Dallas's oldest remaining fire station building still stands at the corner of McKinney Ave. and Leonard and was built in 1892.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] Number 1, and is now a picture framing shop.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] Dallas has many hospitals and several medical research facilities within its city limits.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] One major research center is the Dallas Medical District with the UT Southwestern Medical Center in the Stemmons Corridor, along with the affiliated UT Southwestern Medical School.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] The health care complex includes within its bounds Parkland Memorial Hospital, Children's Medical Center, William P.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] Paul University Hospital), and the William P.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] Dallas also has a VA hospital in the southern portion of the city, the Dallas Veterans Affairs Medical Center.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] The center is home to a Consolidated Mail Outpatient Pharmacy (CMOP), part of an initiative by the Department of Veterans Affairs to provide mail-order prescriptions to veterans using computerization at strategic locations throughout the United States.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] Dallas is served by Dallas Water Utilities, which operates several waste treatment plants and pulls water from several area reservoirs.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] Several companies maintain the city's electric system, including Stream Energy, Cirro Energy and Oncor Electric Delivery, whose parent company, Energy Future Holdings Corporation, has headquarters in the city.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] The city offers garbage pickup and recycling service weekly through its Sanitation Services department.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] Telephone networks, broadband internet, and cable television service are available from several companies, including AT&T, Spectrum, and Verizon FiOS.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] In 2009, 78.5% of Dallas (city) commuters drive to work alone.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] The 2009 mode share for Dallas (city) commuters are 10.7% for carpooling, 3.9% for transit, 1.9% for walking, and .1% for cycling.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] In 2015, the American Community Survey estimated modal shares for Dallas (city) commuters of 75.4% for driving alone, 12.8% for carpooling, 3.5% for riding transit, 1.9% for walking, and .2% for cycling.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] The city of Dallas has a higher than average percentage of households without a car.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] In 2015, 10.2 percent of Dallas households lacked a car, decreased to 9.1 percent in 2016 and to 8.7 percent in 2023.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] Dallas averaged 1.59 cars per household in 2016, compared to a national average of 1.8.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] Dallas is at the confluence of four major interstate highways—Interstates 20, 30, 35E, and 45.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] The Dallas area freeway system is set up in the popular hub-and-spoke system, shaped much like a wagon wheel.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] Starting from the center of the city, a small freeway loop surrounds Downtown, followed by the I-635 loop about 10 miles (16 km) outside Downtown, and ultimately the tolled President George Bush Turnpike.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] Inside these freeway loops are other boulevard- and parkway-style loops, including Loop 12 and Belt Line Road.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] Another beltway around the city upwards of 45 miles (72 km) from Downtown is under plan in Collin County.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] Radiating out of Downtown Dallas's freeway loop are the spokes of the area's highway system—Interstates 30, 35E, and 45, US 75, US 77, US 175, SH Spur 366, the Dallas North Tollway, SH 114, US 80, and US 67.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] Other major highways around the city include SH 183 and Spur 408.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] The recently completed interchange at the intersection of Lyndon B.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] Johnson Freeway (I-635) and the Central Expressway (US 75) has five stacks and is aptly called the High Five Interchange.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] It is one of the few five-level interchanges in Dallas and is one of the largest freeway interchanges in the United States.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] Two commercial airports serve Dallas: Dallas Fort Worth International Airport and Dallas Love Field.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] In addition, Dallas Executive Airport (formerly Redbird Airport), serves as a general aviation airport for the city, and Addison Airport functions similarly just outside the city limits in the suburb of Addison.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] Two more general aviation airports are about 35 miles (56 km) north of Dallas in McKinney, and another two are in Fort Worth, on the west side of the metroplex.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] Alliance Airport, in far North Fort Worth, is a cargo reliever airport to DFW Airport and general aviation facility.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] DFW Airport is in the suburbs slightly north of and equidistant to Downtown Fort Worth and Downtown Dallas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] In terms of size, DFW International is the largest airport in the state, the second largest in the United States, and ninth largest in the world; DFW International Airport is larger than the island of Manhattan.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] In terms of traffic, DFW Airport is the busiest airport in the state, fourth-busiest in the United States, and eleventh-busiest in the world.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] The headquarters of American Airlines, the largest air carrier in the world ahead of United Airlines and Delta Air Lines, is less than one mile (1.6 km) from DFW Airport within Fort Worth's city limits.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] Similarly, Love Field is within Dallas's city limits, about 6 miles (10 km) northwest of Downtown, and is headquarters to Southwest Airlines, the largest domestic airline in the United States.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] Dallas Area Rapid Transit (DART) is the Dallas-area public transportation authority that provides rail, buses and HOV lanes to commuters.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] DART began operating the first light rail system in Texas in 1996, and it is now the largest operator of light rail in the US.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] Today, the system is the seventh-busiest light rail system in the country with approximately 55 stations on 72 miles (116 km) of light rail, and 10 stations on 35 miles (56 km) of commuter rail.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] It includes four light rail lines and a commuter line: the Red Line, the Blue Line, the Green Line, the Orange Line, and the Trinity Railway Express.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] The Red Line travels through Oak Cliff, South Dallas, Downtown, Uptown, North Dallas, Richardson and Plano, while the Blue Line goes through Oak Cliff, Downtown, Uptown, East Dallas, Lake Highlands, and Garland.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] The Red and Blue lines are conjoined between 8th & Corinth Station in Oak Cliff through Mockingbird Station in North Dallas.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] The two lines service Cityplace Station.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] The Green Line serves Carrollton, Farmers Branch, Love Field Airport, Stemmons Corridor, Victory Park, Downtown, Deep Ellum, Fair Park, South Dallas, and Pleasant Grove.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] The Orange Line initially operated as a peak-service line providing extra capacity on portions of the Green and Red Lines (Bachman Station on the Green Line, through the Downtown transit mall, to Parker Road Station on the Red Line making a "U"-shape).
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] However, the first stage of the Orange Line opened on December 6, 2010, extending its west end from Bachman to Belt Line Station in Irving.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] The second and final phase opened in August 2014 and provided DFW Airport with rail service.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] DFW Airport Terminal A station is the terminus for the Orange Line and connects Skylink.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] This provides passengers the convenience of disembarking the DART rail, proceeding to security check-in and immediately boarding Skylink to be quickly transported to their desired terminal.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] The Blue Line has also been extended by 4.5 miles (7.2 km) to serve Rowlett at the Rowlett Park & Ride facility.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] In August 2009, the Regional Transportation Council agreed to seek $96 million in federal stimulus dollars for a trolley project in Dallas and Fort Worth.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] The Oak Cliff Transit Authority took the lead with leaders envisioning a streetcar line that would link Union Station and the Dallas Convention Center in Downtown to Oak Cliff, Methodist Medical Center, and the Bishop Arts District via the Houston Street Viaduct.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] Dallas was awarded a $23 million TIGER grant towards the $58 million Dallas Streetcar Project in February 2010.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] In addition to light rail, Amtrak's *Texas Eagle* also serves Union Station, providing daily service east to Chicago and west to San Antonio, and thrice-weekly service west to Los Angeles.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] The Trinity Rail Express terminates at Union Station and T&P Station.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] The city of Dallas has worked to build Sister & Friendship City relationships around the globe.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] These relationships help create and strengthen partnerships between Dallas and the international community.
[src:baltimore-maryland/dallas-p03] The program aims to build global cooperation at the municipal level by promoting cultural understanding and stimulating economic development between Dallas and its foreign counterparts.
